<FIRST>r w PM-CropAcreage     04-01 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crop Acreage,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Plan to Grow More Corn, Soybeans, Most Other Crops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department survey shows that
farmers intend to boost corn plantings this spring, with easier
federal curbs and higher market prices helping them bounce back
from last year's drought.
   The survey, announced on Friday, showed that farmers intend to
plant 73.3 million acres to corn, up 8 percent from last year.
Soybean plantings are expected to rise 5 percent from 1988 to 61.7
million acres.
   Officials said the report was based on an annual U.S. survey of
about 65,000 farmers in early March. Increases from last year were
also indicated for grain sorghum, wheat _ including winter, durum
and other spring varieties _ tobacco, dry edible beans and sweet
potatoes.
   Farmers indicated they would plant fewer acres this year of
oats, hay, cotton, rice and peanuts.
   If farmers follow through with their plans, the corn acreage
would be the most since 76.7 million acres were planted for the
1986 crop. In 1985, plantings reached 83.4 million acres.
   The planted corn acreage dropped to 60.2 million acres in 1983,
another year of severe drought.
   Last year, of the 67.6 million acres planted, 58.1 million were
harvested for grain, yielding 4.92 billion bushels, down 30 percent
from the 1987 crop. Average yields dropped to 84.6 bushels per acre
from a record of 119.4 bushels in 1987.
   There was no indication of 1988 production in the report. Winter
wheat output will be indicated by the USDA for the first time on
May 11 and corn figures in August, along with soybeans, cotton and
other spring-planted crops.
   Total wheat plantings for this year's harvest was indicated at
74.3 million acres, up by more than 13 percent from last year.
Winter wheat was reported at 54.7 million acres, up 12 per cent;
durum, 3.86 million, up 16 percent; and other spring-planted wheat,
15.7 million acres, up 17 percent.
   Officials cautioned that the actual acreage planted by farmers
this spring ``may vary from intentions because of the effects of
weather, availability of production inputs, changes in market
conditions prior to planting'' and the impact of the USDA report
itself.
   With production cut by last year's drought, market prices of
grains and soybeans rose sharply. The USDA also relaxed
acreage-reduction requirements under wheat and feed grains programs
for 1989.
   Preliminary price figures for March showed on Thursday that the
average farm price of wheat was $4.16 per bushel, up from $2.74 a
year ago. Corn was reported at $2.61 against $1.86 in March 1988,
and soybeans were $7.57 per bushel, compared with $6.05 a year
earlier.
   Other crops included in the survey report:
   _Cotton plantings, 11 million acres, down 12 percent from 1988.
   _Sorghum, 11.8 million acres, up 14 percent.
   _Barley, 9.62 million acres, down 1 percent.
   _Oats, 13.2 million acres, down 5 percent.
   _Hay, 63.1 million acres, down 4 percent.
   _Rice, 2.86 million acres, down 2 percent.
   _Peanuts, 1.64 million acres, down 1 percent.
   _Tobacco, 713,000 acres, up 13 percent.
   _Dry edible beans, 1.67 million acres, up 11 percent.
   _Sweet potatoes, 94,000 acres, up 2 percent.
</TEXT>
