<FIRST>r w PM-FCC-Minorities     04-01 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FCC-Minorities,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minority-Preference Rules Held Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission is being
forced to review its policy of favoring minorities in the sale of
``distressed'' radio and TV stations because a court says the
program is unconstitutional.
   The FCC's 1978 ``distress sale'' rules, which allow quick sales
at reduced rates of defunct or disenfranchised stations to blacks,
Hispanics and other minorities, violate the equal protection
provisions of the Fifth Amendment to the Constitution, a federal
appeals court said Friday.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, in a 2-1
vote, overturned a purchase after a Hartford, Conn., broadcaster
said he should have been able to try to buy a station being offered
in a distress sale.
   The ruling is at odds with Congress, which in December 1987
refused _ with then-President Reagan concurring _ to allow the FCC
to consider changing the policy.
   The FCC had said it wanted to review the policy after the
appeals court in 1986 rejected a sale based on the agency's
``comparative preference'' program of giving special treatment to
women seeking FM station licenses.
   But after Congress acted, the FCC voted 3-0 in February 1988 to
reaffirm the distress sale and female preference policies.
   It was not clear Friday how the commission would react to the
latest remand.
   FCC Commissioner Patricia Diaz Dennis said she strongly
supported minority entry into broadcasting and that the court had
struck down a program mandated by Congress. ``We are now between
the proverbial rock and a hard place,'' she said.
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick also said he supported ensuring
minority participation in broadcasting, but also that ``race alone
should not control the licensing of broadcast stations.''
   The Media Access Center, which filed a friend-of-the-court brief
in the case, said the FCC policy had worked well and the court
``made a mistake.''
   Andrew Schwartzman, the center's executive director, said ``we
expect that Congress or the Supreme Court will reinstate the FCC's
policy.''
   The FCC in 1984 denied Alan Shurberg and Shurberg Broadcasting a
chance to compete for the purchase of WHCT-TV in Hartford from the
station's owner.
   The FCC also affirmed that a rival for the Hartford station,
Astroline Communications Company Limited Partnership, was a
minority enterprise and not a sham, as Shurberg contended.
   The appeals court Friday said the FCC policy did not meet
previous Supreme Court tests of minority set-aside programs,
including one that preferences be given to minorities only after
race-neutral efforts to increase minority ownership had failed.
   ``The distress sale policy is not narrowly tailored to remedy
past discrimination ... and it provides no procedures for ensuring
that the policy's beneficiaries have actually suffered from the
effects of past discrimination,'' Judge Laurence H. Silberman said
in the majority opinion.
   Chief Judge Patricia M. Wald dissented, saying the distress sale
policy legally worked to ensure diversity in programming and
ownership and that it was ``narrowly tailored to address the
critical entry barriers to minority participation in media
ownership while imposing only minimal burdens on innocent third
parties.''
   Shurberg, speaking by phone from Hartford, said he was
``delighted'' with the court's ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
