<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 0149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     04-01 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESWICK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmer Richard Panza doesn't understand why
local tax officials won't let him pay back taxes with a little
piggy that has yet to go market.
   Panza said he'll try to pay the debt again Tuesday by offering
his pig, Art, to the city.
   Earlier this week, Panza donned his overalls, placed Art in a
pickup truck and parked it outside the office of District
Magistrate Art Sabulsky.
   ``Them pigs are my net profit,'' he told the magistrate,
insisting it's legal to pay with pork. A Harmar Township ordinance
allows him to pay with his income, which happens to be pigs, he
said.
   Sabulsky ordered Panza to release his personal records so tax
collectors could calculate how much he owes the township and the
area school district.
   ``I've been fighting this for 13 years,'' Panza said. ``First of
all, they're being a pig about all these taxes. You've got to pay
property tax, school tax, township tax, and then they want to tax
your net profit. There's nothing left for you.''
   Sabulsky wouldn't say whether he'll accept the pig as payment.
</TEXT>
