<FIRST>r a PM-ColorClash     04-01 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Color Clash,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philosophers To Debate On The Existence Of Color</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roses are red, violets are blue. ...
   Or are they?
   Philosophers from around the country will gather in Ann Arbor
next week to discuss whether color is only in the eye of the
beholder.
   The eighth annual colloquium in philosophy April 6-7 at the
University of Michigan will include presentations by professors
from Princeton, Syracuse and Nebraska universities, as well as
Michigan.
   ``What's at issue is whether we have color in the world in the
same way that we have shape in the world,'' said Stephen L.
Darwall, the philosophy department chairman at Michigan.
   When it comes to color, philosophers tend to fall into two camps.
   Some argue that colors have an objective existence independent
of our perception of them, Darwall said.
   Others argue that color is an illusion; that an object's
characteristics cause it to reflect light a certain way, making
people believe they are seeing a certain color, he added.
   The question of color is recognized as a primary element in the
debate between philosophers supporting a realistic outlook and
their counterparts advocating an anti-realist point of view,
Darwall said.
   ``It's a litmus test for different philosophical points of
view,'' Darwall said of the color clash.
   Not much is expected to be resolved at the conference, Darwall
said.
   ``It's not the case in philosophy that we get discoveries that
are recognized instantly by all credible philosophers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
