<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Wash-Primary     04-01 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wash-Primary,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Lawmakers Approve Presidential Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington state on Friday became
America's 36th state with a presidential primary, setting up hopes
for a regional set of primaries that would attract candidates to
the Pacific Northwest.
   The Senate voted 38 to 10 for an initiative submitted by the
people after the Legislature had balked for years at the idea of
eliminating the state's much-maligned caucus system of choosing
national convention delegates.
   As drafted, the legislation would enable Washington to join
Oregon, Idaho and Montana on the date Oregon uses, the fourth
Tuesday in May.
   Supporters of the measure said evangelist Pat Robertson's
victory in last spring's caucuses embarrassed the state into
accepting a primary. Washington, usually seen as a moderate,
politically progressive state, carried the nation's largest
Robertson delegation to the national GOP convention in New Orleans
last August.
   The measure already had cleared the House by an even greater
margin. Since Gov. Booth Gardner's signature was not required,
Initiative 99 was delivered directly to the secretary of state
minutes after passage.
   Champagne corks popped at an impromptu celebration staged by
Secretary of State Ralph Munro, a long-term sponsor who exulted,
``It's finally over!''
   The state will have a primary every presidential year, beginning
in 1992.
   Oregon is toying with changes in its primary date, and there's
no definite agreement for a four-state Super Tuesday, but the
Washington legislation gives the secretary of state flexibility to
set a mutually agreeable date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
