<HEAD>Campaign May Have Accepted Illegal Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 presidential campaign of Sen. Bob
Dole may have unknowingly accepted up to $15,000 in illegal
corporate contributions that were channeled through individuals.
   Dole, R-Kan., issued a statement Friday saying the FBI had
contacted him last week asking assistance in an investigation and
that he has ordered the filing of a complaint with the Federal
Election Commission.
   The complaint will ask the commission for advice on who should
receive refunds of such contributions to the Dole for President
Committee.
   ``As part of Dole for President's cooperation with a federal
investigation into matters totally unrelated to my presidential
campaign, it became apparent that DFP may have received tainted
money,'' Dole said.
   ``My campaign is not the subject of this investigation, nor did
it have any knowledge of these allegations,'' he said. ``If true, I
strongly condemn the illegal activities.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FMac Changes Mortgage Rules</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. is
changing some mortgage rules to help some homeowners to get rid of
their private mortgage insurance earlier.
   When a home buyer puts less than 20 percent down on a house, the
agency, known as Freddie Mac, requires the buyer to get mortgage
insurance to guarantee mortgage payments.
   But the insurance fee boosts the monthly payment required until
the homebuyer builds up equity representing 20 percent of the
home's value.
   Previously, Freddie Mac required that a mortgage be held at
least seven years before the insurance could be lifted even if the
value of the home soars and the owner's equity rises above 80
percent.
   Under the change announced Friday, the insurance can be lifted
in two to five years, depending on circumstances and provided that
mortgage payments have been made on time.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Picnic to Mark Opening of White House Horseshoe Pit</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush invited several governors and
nine top players from the National Horseshoe Pitchers Association
to a picnic today to mark the official opening of the White House's
horseshoe pit.
   The president, an avid player, had a pit set up near the
swimming pool on the west side of the Executive Mansion.
   Bush invited Govs. Kay Orr of Nebraska, James Blanchard of
Michigan, Carroll Campbell of South Carolina, Michael Castle of
Delaware; Guy Hunt of Alabama; Judd Gregg of New Hampshire,
Madeleine Kunin of Vermont, John McKernan of Maine; William Donald
Schaefer of Maryland and Steve Cowper of Alaska.
