<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>HUD Gives City One Week to Clean Up Housing</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development has given the District of Columbia one week to improve
its long-troubled public housing program or face the potential loss
of federal home modernization funds.
   ``The D.C. government has purported to be getting a handle on
public housing for nearly a decade,'' wrote HUD field manager
Margaret White in a recent letter sent to city officials. ``But
sadly, the effort expended has been virtually to no avail. ...
Concrete results are significantly overdue.''
   Ms. White's order set a Friday deadline for having the city
speed up its repair schedule for vacant units.
   HUD cannot deny payment of the city's operating subsidy, which
was $28 million last year, because of poor performance. But White
said her office reviews requests from the city to make
recommendations to regional housing officials on whether to award
modernization funds sought by the city.
   White's order sets deadlines for the district to meet several
federal standards used to measure the proficiency of housing
authorities. She cited the District for slow ``turnaround time'' in
filling vacated units, ineffective maintenance, low financial
reserves, excessive vacancies and slow rent collection.
</TEXT>
