<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights activist Dick Gregory says
blacks have not learned to exercise their economic power to bring
about social change.
   Gregory, speaking Friday at Miami University, said that if
blacks in the United States constituted a separate nation, ``we
would be the fifth or sixth economic power in the world. We spend
more in the United States than all of Europe.''
   Blacks buy 28 percent of the Cadillacs sold ``and don't have the
nerve to ask for 28 percent of the jobs'' making Cadillacs, he said.
   Gregory also said that although blacks make up the largest block
of Americans without cable television, ``we never demand that the
networks cater to us.''
   His speech was part of a weekend marking the 25th anniversary of
a project that trained workers to go to Mississippi and register
blacks to vote. The training took place at Western College for
Women, now a part of Miami University. Two such workers were among
three people killed in a shooting on which the current movie
``Mississippi Burning'' is based.
