<FIRST>u i PM-Egypt-US     04-01 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-US,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Wants United States To Increase Pressure On Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buoyed by support from key Arab leaders,
President Hosni Mubarak leaves for Washington today to tell U.S.
officials they must move quickly to persuade Israel to talk to the
PLO, Egyptian officials said.
   The four-day U.S. visit, Mubarak's seventh since taking office
in 1981, follows six weeks of intensive diplomatic exchanges
initiated by the Egyptian leader. The activity brought leaders from
the Soviet Union, Israel, Jordan, Saudi Arabia and the Palestine
Liberation Organization to Egypt.
   Mubarak will meet with President Bush on Monday.
   ``Mubarak is carrying to the United States for the first time a
unified Arab position for the achievement of Arab-Israeli peace,''
said a senior government official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``This gives Egypt greater credibility.''
   The unified position was forged in Mubarak's Egyptian talks
during the past week with Jordan's King Hussein, PLO leader Yasser
Arafat and King Fahd of Saudi Arabia.
   The official said Mubarak will argue a need for speedy movement
by the United States to persuade Israel to accept an international
peace conference and negotiations with the PLO.
   Israel fears it would be pressured into concessions as a result
of such a conference, and it rejects Arafat's group as terrorists.
   The conference, under U.N. auspices, would group parties to the
conflict, including the PLO, and the permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council: the United States, the Soviet Union, Britain,
France and China.
   The Egyptian official also said Mubarak and his Arab backers
would like to see Bush use his influence with Israel to convene an
international conference before the end of this year.
   U.S. Ambassador Frank Wisner, in prepared remarks for the local
media on Mubarak's visit, dampened hopes for quick breakthrough as
a result of U.S. efforts.
   ``It will not be easy to arrive at quick results,'' the U.S.
diplomat said. ``What we should do is build confidence to bring the
parties to the negotiating table.''
   He seemed to be referring to a desire by Washington for
reciprocal moves by Israel and the PLO to stop violence in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Stip. A Palestinian uprising in
those territories has killed more than 415 Palestinians and 18
Israelis since it began in December 1987.
   Mubarak's Washington talks also will deal with U.S. economic and
military aid to Egypt and ways of easing Cairo's foreign debt
burden.
   The United States has held up $230 million in cash aid for Egypt
in 1988 and 1989, saying Egypt failed to adopt ``significant''
economic reforms.
   Mubarak says he agrees on the need for economic reforms but
disagrees with the United States on the pace of such steps. He
fears austerity measures might trigger street violence.
   Egypt's foreign debt totals about $44 billion.
</TEXT>
