<FIRST>r a PM-FourSlain     04-01 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Four Slain,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Bodies Found Stuffed in Car In Norfolk, Va.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of four young men were found
stuffed in the a parked car in what police said was the city's
worst murder case in 13 years.
   Police called by an apartment building resident discovered one
body Friday in the car's back seat with its sneaker-clad feet
sticking out of the rear window, said Cpl. Robert Haynes, a police
spokesman.
   A second body was found underneath the first victim, and two
other corpses were found in the trunk of the silver Volvo with
Delaware license plates, Haynes said. The car was left in the
building's parking lot, he said.
   The victims were black and in their late teens or early 20s, he
said. They had yet to be identified, and police did not have
suspects.
   ``There were signs of violence, blood,'' Haynes said.
   A witness who asked not to be identified said stuffed teddy
bears were piled around one victim in the back seat.
   Police said violent crime is unusual in the Norview East
neighborhood with frame cottages and ranch homes, but the parking
lot is within blocks of the low-income Lakeland Apartments, a
frequent destination for police.
   Haynes said the crime was the city's worst mass murder since May
1976, when a 21-year-old man walked into a crowded downtown
nightspot and opened fire, killing four people and wounding three
before killing himself.
</TEXT>
