<FIRST>r a AM-Mummy-Sentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0417 04-01 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mummy-Sentencing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0417,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced for Forgery in Mummy Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `It was...' to restore dropped words. Edits to
trim.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dentist has been sentenced to 30
months' probation for forgery in a bizarre case involving a dead
man whose mummified remains were tended by his family for nine
years.
   Knox County Judge Daniel Roberts opted for probation for Richard
Kunce, 57, who lived for two years with the family of the dead man,
Carl Stevens. State's Attorney Ray Kimbell had recommended a
three-year prison term.
   Kunce, who has lost his license to practice dentistry, was
convicted recently of witnessing a forgery of Stevens' signature,
which was placed on a document by the widow, Carole Stevens.
   The judge noted at Thursday's hearing that Mrs. Stevens was
sentenced to 24 months of probation after she pleaded guilty to two
counts of forgery in the case last year.
   During the hearing, both sides recalled how Carl Stevens' body
was tended by his family and Kunce as if he were still alive.
   Stevens, a diabetic, died in 1979 after joining a holistic
health cult and halting his daily insulin injections. In January
1988, authorities discovered his body in the Stevens home.
   Kunce lived at the home from summer 1986 until the body was
discovered.
   Kimbell argued that Kunce should be given a stiff sentence
because he harmed Mrs. Stevens' two teen-age children by promoting
the ``strange idea'' that Stevens was alive as his mummified corpse
remained in the home.
   Kunce said he signed as a witness to the 1984 document that gave
Mrs. Stevens her husband's power of attorney because she wanted to
refinance her home.
   Kunce said his immediate plans are to return to Corpus Christi,
Texas, to live with his sister, and perhaps teach nutrition or
practice dentistry if he can renew his license.
   ``I've got to get on with my life,'' he said. ``I think I'll
start by going fishing.''
</TEXT>
