<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 0527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FusionReport     04-01 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Report,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Fusion Experiment Gives Hope, But Far From Proven, Scientist
Cautions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scientist who reported that a simple apparatus
may create fusion power at room temperature said his work gives
hope for a new energy source, but warned that ``fusion fever''
enthusiasm is premature.
   ``I think we have a new approach to fusion,'' but it is too
early to say whether it will prove useful for generating
electricity, said Steven Jones of Brigham Young University in
Provo, Utah.
   The results still must withstand scientific scrutiny and be
confirmed by other scientists, and until that happens, ``don't sell
your oil well,'' Jones said.
   Even if the results hold up, it would take many years before the
process could be put to practical use, Jones said Friday at a
physics colloquium and a later press conference at Columbia
University in New York.
   Fusion is the process that powers the sun and stars, where
tremendous amounts of energy are released when the nucleus, or
core, of one hydrogen atom fuses with the nucleus of another
hydrogen atom.
   In contrast, today's nuclear power plants get energy from
fission, which is the splitting of atoms.
   Scientists hope to harness fusion power, saying it provides an
environmentally benign energy source with a virtually unlimited
source of fuel: ``heavy'' hydrogen, which occurs naturally in water.
   Standard fusion experiments use extremely high temperatures to
get the hydrogen atoms to fuse. But Jones and scientists at the
University of Utah announced recently that they had independently
found a simple way to produce fusion reactions at room temperature.
   Essentially, they used electrical current to herd hydrogen atoms
into metal electrodes, where the hydrogen atoms apparently fused.
   The University of Utah researchers said their apparatus produced
four times as much energy as it consumed. Jones, in contrast, said
the Brigham Young device appeared to produce only about one
ten-trillionth of the energy put into it.
   Jones said he had not read the other team's scientific paper and
could not explain the difference.
   The Brigham Young apparatus included a pair of electrodes
immersed in ``heavy water,'' in which hydrogen atoms contain an
extra particle called a neutron in the nucleus. This kind of
hydrogen is called deuterium.
   When low voltage was applied to the electrodes, deuterium nuclei
were drawn into one of the electrodes. There, they apparently
crowded together closely enough to fuse, Jones said.
   Researchers calculated that two fusions occurred every five
seconds, which would yield an energy output of one ten-trillionth
of a watt. One watt is about enough to run an electric toothbrush.
   The evidence for fusion was that the apparatus emitted neutrons,
Jones said. That happened when the nuclei were driven into
electrodes made from either titanium or palladium, with titanium
giving the better results, Jones said.
   ``We don't really have a good theory'' to explain the fusion,
Jones said. Perhaps deuterium nuclei are forced close enough to
fuse while hopping from site to site within the crystal structure
of the electrode, he said.
   He calls the fusion approach piezonuclear fusion, because
``piezo'' means ``to squeeze.''
   A similar process may cause part of the heat at the Earth's
core, he said.
   In Salt Lake City, one of two researchers who first announced
the discovery, B. Stanley Pons, said Friday he had found no
chemical explanation for the process by which he achieved
sustained, controlled nuclear fusion in a simple experiment.
   ``It cannot be explained by any known chemical process,'' said
Pons, a professor at the University of Utah. ``I can conceive of no
other process other than a nuclear process'' to explain the results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 0524EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SavannahRiver     04-01 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savannah River,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>SRP Workers Get $80 Million in Severance, Vacation Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. RIGSBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 6,500 Savannah River Plant workers got
$80 million in severance and vacation pay as operator Du Pont
handed over operation of the nuclear weapons plant to Westinghouse
Electric today.
   E.I. du Pont de Nemours &amp; Co., which built the plant near the
Georgia border and managed it for the government for 38 years,
announced last October it was not renewing its contract with the
Department of Energy amid continuing reports of safety problems at
the Aiken plant and others around the nation, including those in
Rocky Flats, Colo., and Fernald, Ohio.
   Du Pont issued the checks Thursday and Friday, even though most
employees will stay on. About 1,200 workers decided to retire.
   Many of the severance and vacation checks ranged from $20,000 to
$30,000, said Scott Murphy of the plant credit union.
   ``I'm crying all the way to the bank,'' joked 22-year Du Pont
employee Henry H. Franks, who said he was going to use his
$10,000-plus check to buy a new tractor.
   ``It's like Christmas has come at the end of March,'' June
Murff, president of the Greater Aiken Chamber of Commerce, said
Friday.
   The Savannah River Plant is the nation's only manufacturer of
tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen used to make nuclear
weapons at other government defense plants. Its three reactors have
been idled for nearly a year because of safety and structural
problems.
   Under the new arrangement, Westinghouse will be paid by the
government for managing the plant.
</TEXT>
