<FIRST>r a PM-SnowWhite     04-01 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Snow White,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney and Academy Huddle Over Snow White Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. and the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences are trying to amicably resolve a dispute
over a Snow White lookalike's appearance in the Oscar show's
opening number.
   The two met Friday, but there was no indication Disney was ready
to drop its federal trademark infringement lawsuit against the
academy.
   ``We are in talks with Disney and we won't have any comment
until they are completed,'' said academy spokesman Bruce Davis.
   Fiercely protective of its image and copyrights, Disney filed
the lawsuit in U.S. District Court on Thursday, alleging that Oscar
producers did not have permission to use the Disney-copyrighted
fairy tale character.
   The broadcast, seen in an estimated 27 million American homes,
began Wednesday night with actress Eileen Bowman, dressed as Snow
White, following a chorus line of dancing stars into the Shrine
Auditorium.
   In a squeaky Betty Boop voice, Bowman then launched into a
rendition of ``We Only Have Stars for You,'' to the tune of ``I
Only Have Eyes for You.'' She also sang a rendition of ``Proud
Mary'' with actor Rob Lowe.
   Disney spokesman Erwin Okun said the performance was
unflattering to the beloved character, and Disney President Frank
Wells said the matter could have been settled without litigation if
the academy had publicly apologized.
   ``For its own reasons, however, the academy unfortunately did
not accede to our request,'' Wells said.
   The Oscar show's producer, Allan Carr, declined to comment
because of the pending lawsuit.
   All media queries were referred to Davis, who said it was
strange that the use of the character had not been cleared with
Disney.
   ``Obtaining rights is one of the things we do routinely,'' Davis
said. ``Every little three seconds of music, or a film clip, has to
get cleared. Yes, it is very puzzling. We are exploring the reasons
for that.''
   ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs'' was released by Disney in
1937 and was the studio's first feature-length animated cartoon.
Critics praised the film, calling it a turning point in Disney's
career and a milestone in movie history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
