<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence     04-01 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Violence,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clashes In Beirut, Sidon Leave 2 Dead, 15 Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Syrian gunners dueled with
howitzers and rocket launchers around Beirut today despite a United
Nations plea for a cease-fire in the 25-day confrontation. Police
said nine people were wounded.
   The latest casualties brought the overall toll to 129 people
killed and 418 wounded in the clashes between Gen. Michel Aoun's
predominantly Christian army units and an alliance of Syrian troops
and militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party.
   Police said two people were killed and six wounded in a six-hour
clash in the southern port of Sidon between the dominant Sunni
Moslem militia of Mustafa Saad and a splinter faction.
   A police spokesman said the leader of the breakaway faction,
Mohammed Hankir, ``surrendered to Saad's militia at 8 a.m. ... Life
is normal in Sidon.''
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules, said
Syrian army gunners pounded the Christian heartland northeast of
Beirut with shells and rockets before dawn.
   He said gunners of Aoun's 20,000-strong Christian army responded
to Syrian fire coming from Moslem west Beirut, the Druse central
mountains and Chouf mountains southeast of the capital as well as
the Bekaa valley in east Lebanon.
   Several 155mm U.S.-designed howitzer shells, fired by Aoun's
gunners, exploded in residential districts of Syrian-policed west
Beirut in the pre-dawn shelling, the spokesman said.
   A Christian military source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the Syrians today deployed 180mm Soviet-designed howitzers for
the first time since the current round of violence broke out March
8.
   ``They are using the heavy howitzers to knock out army bunkers
and fortifications. It seems they want to use it to demolish vital
utilities as well,'' the source said.
   The clashes erupted after Aoun clamped a blockade on militia-run
illegal ports in an effort to reactivate tax-collection at the five
government harbors along the 130-mile coastline.
   Aoun escalated the crisis by declaring a ``war of liberation''
against Syria's 40,000 troops deployed in predominantly Moslem
areas of Lebanon since 1976 under a peacekeeping mandate from the
Arab League.
   Hostilities have persisted despite a truce called by the Arab
League on Tuesday and a unilateral cease-fire declared Wednesday by
Aoun, a Maronite Catholic who also heads the Christian cabinet in
Lebanon's dual government.
   The U.N. Security Council on Friday issued a cease-fire appeal
urging ``all the parties to put an immediate end to the
confrontations, to respond favorably to the appeals launched for an
effective cease-fire and to avoid any action that might further
heighten the tension.''
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the rival Moslem
cabinet, today called for ``a mechanism to monitor implementation
of the cease-fire calls'' along with a settlement of the ports
controversy.
   The political crisis threatens to cement Lebanon's de faction
division into Christian and Moslem sectors after 14 years of civil
war.
</TEXT>
