<FIRST>r a PM-HighwayKillings     04-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Highway Killings,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Find Eighth Body In Highway Killings Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An eighth body has been found along the
same highway where seven others have been discovered since July,
and authorities are urging the person who wrote them a letter
telling of its whereabouts to come forward.
   Two boys found the eighth body, that of a young woman, Friday
along Route 88 about 25 feet from the road, police said.
   ``Indications are that this is linked to the other seven and we
do in fact have our eighth victim in the highway murders,'' said
Jim Martin, a spokesman for the district attorney.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald Pina said the woman
appeared to be in her late teens to early 20s.
   The first seven victims had been involved in prostitution or
drugs in New Bedford's Weld Square area, according to family
members and police. The first victim was found in July. The most
recent was discovered Tuesday.
   Pina said his office got an anonymous letter two weeks ago with
information about the missing women.
   The district attorney said the letter writer offered quite a bit
of information about the missing women.
   ``They indicated roughly where the body would be on 88 and said
they were hesitant to come forward,'' Pina said. ``But they said
they would possibly come forward if we found a body on 88. Well,
it's here. The body is on 88.''
   Martin said the remains were taken to St. Luke's Hospital in New
Bedford, where an autospy would be performed.
</TEXT>
