<FIRST>u i PM-Malawi-Thatcher 1stLd-Writethry   04-01 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malawi-Thatcher, 1st Ld-Writethry,a0447,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Hopes For Mediating Role In Southern Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS three grafs to UPDATE with Thatcher arriving in Namibia.
Picks up graf 4 pvs, `On her ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
today left Malawi convinced she has a role to play in seeking a
political settlement in South Africa.
   Malawi President Hastings Kamuzu Banda, who is in his 80s,
kissed the British leader's hand as she curtsied to him in a
departure ceremony at Chileka airport near the commercial capital
of Blantyre.
   Thatcher's destination was kept secret, evidently for security
reasons, but she arrived shortly after noon today in Windhoek,
Namibia, on the first day of that southwest African territory's
process toward independence from South African control. Among those
she was expected to meet was South African Foreign Minister Pik
Botha.
   On her current African swing, the British premier has visited
Morocco, Nigeria, Zimbabwe and Malawi.
   On each leg of the tour she has expressed hope that conditions
are right for a negotiated end to conflict in Southern Africa with
Britain playing a role in any possible political breakthrough in
white-ruled South Africa.
   At a banquet hosted by Banda at his hilltop palace outside
Blantyre late Friday, Thatcher said she was visiting a continent
torn by strife but she came ``with the conviction that this is the
time of new hope for Southern Africa''.
   She cited the U.N-supervised independence plan for Namibia
starting today as evidence of a conciliatory mood in the region
which secured a timetable for the withdrawal of Cuban troops from
Angola, Namibia's northern neighbor, and South Africa's withdrawal
from Namibia.
   Thatcher said within South Africa itself, ``one sees a growing
acceptance that discrimination based on race and color must end and
will end, that black South Africans must be allowed to play their
part in politics and government.''
   Britain has said it is prepared assist in mediation efforts in
South Africa on condition jailed African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela is released first and that the guerrilla leader
renounces violence.
   Thatcher has argued that Britain has unique expertise based on
experience gained from relinquising power in its former African
colonies, particularly Zimbabwe.
   An all-party conference chaired by Britian in 1979 ended a
seven-year guerrilla war in white-ruled Rhodesia and led to the
birth of the independent nation of Zimbabwe the following year.
   On her African tour, Thatcher has restated he opposition to an
economic blockade of South Africa, contending that sanctions would
hurt South Africa's 28 million blacks the most.
   In Namibia, ``now there must be free and fair elections just
like those which Britain organized in Zimbabwe nine years ago,''
she said.
   Thatcher was expected to hold talks with United Nations
officials in Namibia later today and visit British troops in a U.N.
peacekeeping force in the territory which has been controlled by
South Africa since World War 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
