<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-01 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Weather Returns To Parts of Midwest, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter weather returned today to parts of the Northeast and
Midwest, with storms dumping snow in upstate New York and delaying
spring field work for Ohio farmers.
   Low pressure off the New England coast brought snow to parts of
the lower Great Lakes region and northern New England.
   In upstate New York, snowstorms lingered after leaving up to 7
inches of snow in Batavia and 5 inches in Rochester, where police
reported numerous accidents as drivers coped with the reprise of
winter weather.
   ``Cars are off the road everywhere,'' said a state trooper in
the Rochester suburb of Henrietta. ``I don't know if it's the
busiest day of the year, but it's been busy. People forgot how to
drive. You get a couple of nice days and now it's winter again.''
   In Ohio, the cold weather slowed the growth of wheat and
pastures across the state. More than 8 inches of snow fell in
Youngstown, and snowstorms remained today in much of the Ohio
Valley.
   Elsewhere, widely scattered rain showers extended mainly from
eastern Nevada to western South Dakota and western Nebraska and a
few showers and thunderstorms dampened southern Florida.
   Today's forecast called for rain from New Jersey to Maine along
the East Coast; snow in the central and northern Appalachians; rain
and snow showers in the upper Mississippi Valley; widespread rain
in the Pacific Northwest; and showers across the northern and
central Rockies.
   Highs were expected to be in the 30s in much of Minnesota and
from the central Appalachians across upstate New York to northern
New England; 40s and 50s from the Pacific Northwest across the
northern and central Rockies, the northern Plains, the upper
Mississippi Valley, most of the Great Lakes region and the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys to the middle and northern Atlantic Coast; 80s
from southwest Texas across southern New Mexico to southern
Arizona; and 90s in the desert Southwest.
   Elsewhere, highs were predicted to be in the 60s and 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 13
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., to 78 at Palm Springs, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 42 fair; Boston 36 drizzle; Buffalo 32 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 51 fair; Cincinnati 34 snow; Cleveland 32 snow;
Detroit 31 snow; Miami 71 fair; New York 42 windy; Philadelphia 42
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 32 snow; Portland, Maine 33 drizzle;
Washington 43 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 43 cloudy; Chicago 31 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
49 fair; Denver 45 fair; Des Moines 36 fair; Indianapolis 34
cloudy; Kansas City 40 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 26 partly cloudy;
Nashville 33 fair; New Orleans 52 fair; St. Louis 38 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 52 fair; Anchorage 33 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 71 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 72 fair; Salt
Lake City 42 cloudy; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 50 fair;
Seattle 41 cloudy.
   _Canada: Toronto 32 cloudy.
</TEXT>
