<HEAD>Three U.N. Peacekeepers Die in Traffic Accidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of the U.N. peacekeeping
force, two British and a Bangladeshi, have died as a result of two
separate traffic accidents, a U.N. spokesman said today.
   The two Britons, whose names and ranks were not released, were
killed Friday in a one-car crash while they were driving north from
Windhoek to work on a communications system for the U.N. force. Two
other Britons in the vehicle suffered only minor injuries, said
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard.
   He said the commander of Bangladesh's contingent, Lt. Col. Fazil
Karim of Dacca, died Friday from severe head injuries suffered in a
collision Wednesday.
   More than 20 countries have contributed personnel to the U.N.
force. It formally started duty today in overseeing a transition to
independence from South Africa.
