<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-Strike     04-01 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Strike,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Battle Dockworkers, Students Outside Shipyard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of dockworkers and students
armed with clubs, firebombs and rocks fought police for the second
consecutive day today, protesting a police crackdown that ended a
prolonged strike at the nation's largest shipyard.
   About 3,500 protesters took to the streets of Ulsan, about 150
miles southeast of Seoul, in scattered protests, news reports said.
   Police fired tear gas and charged the protesters, who responded
with rocks and firebombs in hit-and-run battles, according to the
South Korean news agency Yonhap. The report said nothing of arrests
or injuries.
   Thousands of riot police guarded Ulsan's Hyundai shipyard, where
the strike was broken up, and established checkpoints around bus
terminals and on roads leading to the shipyard to block
sympathizers from joining the protesters, it said.
   In Seoul, about 1,000 students supporting Hyundai strikers
battled riot police around Hanyang University for an hour after
burning effigies of President Roh Tae-woo and Hyundai.
   The Ulsan shipyard is owned by the Hyundai group, one of the
largest conglomerates in South Korea. One of its subsidiaries
manufactures cars for the U.S. auto market.
   Masked students brandishing firebombs streamed out of the gates,
yelling ``Down with Roh Tae-woo, who stifles workers' rights!''
About 2,000 riot police sealed off the campus and fired hundreds of
tear gas shells.
   There were no immediate reports of arrests and injuries in Seoul.
   Operations of the Hyundai shipyard remained slow, although more
than half of its 22,000-member work force showed up for work today.
   Riot police stormed the shipyard Thursday in a land, sea and air
attack to end the strike, whose violence injured about 400 people
since December.
   Hyundai's trouble began last Dec. 12, when militant workers
broke away from a company-sanctioned union and organized a separate
group, demanding pay hikes and better working conditions.
   The police intervention triggered violent protests in Seoul and
other cities by strike sympathizers who accused the government of
suppressing free labor and protecting conglomerates at the cost of
workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
