<DOCNO> AP890401-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 0739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TrailofTears     04-01 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trail of Tears,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cherokees Mark 150th Anniversary of Beginning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAHLEQUAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cherokee Indians from across the country
are observing the 150th anniversary of the Trail of Tears, the
forced march from their Southeastern homeland that claimed an
estimated 4,000 lives.
   ``In Cherokee memory it is only a short time ago,'' Wilma
Mankiller, chief of the Cherokee Nation of Oklahoma, told about 300
people gathered Friday on the lawn of the old Cherokee national
capitol in this northeast Oklahoma city of 10,000. The observance
ends today.
   The forced relocation of much of the tribe to Oklahoma ended in
late 1839. Of the estimated 4,000 Cherokees who died, many were
buried in unmarked graves.
   ``And yet here we are. Here we are. Despite everything that has
happened to us,'' Ms. Mankiller said.
   Today, the 93,000-member Cherokee Tribe is the nation's second
largest, behind the Navajos.
   Ms. Mankiller and Chief Jonathan Taylor of the eastern band of
Cherokees from Cherokee, N.C., planted an oak tree on the capitol
grounds ``in memory of many people who were on the trail who did
not make it to the new home,'' said Deputy Chief John Ketcher of
Tahlequah.
   Officials had made it clear the prayers and speeches were to be
more a memorial service than a celebration, but some said their
ancestors' travails 150 years ago were not being emphasized enough.
   Pat Moss of Stilwell, vice chairman of Native Americans for a
Clean Environment, asked that April 1 be recognized as an
international day of sorrow in memory of those who died on the
Trail of Tears.
   ``The forced relocation of Cherokee and other indigenous people,
known as the Trail of Tears, was an act of genocide,'' Moss said.
   ``While it is a very, very sad time in our history, I still
believe we can draw strength from our ancestors,'' said Ms.
Mankiller. ``I've been able to draw strength from that terrible
time in our history.''
   She emphasized that when they were relocated the Cherokees were
a civilized, self-governing tribe.
   The tribe survived the Trail of Tears to reform its government,
establish schools, and erect civic buildings in northeast Oklahoma.
   However, in 1906 the tribe's land was taken away; members were
given individual allotments. The Cherokees had no constitutional
tribal government until 1971, when the capitol was re-established
in Tahlequah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
