<FIRST>u i PM-RefugeeMassacre     04-01 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugee Massacre,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Pirates Massacre 45 Boat People, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai pirates raided a boat full of
Vietnamese refugees in the South China Sea, massacred 45 of them
and kidnapped about 11 women, officials said today.
   An old man and young boy were the only survivors of the attack,
which occurred within about the last seven days, said the
officials, who work with refugees and who spoke with The Associated
Press on condition of anonymity.
   The pirates stormed the unarmed boat, slashed the passengers
with knives and threw their bodies overboard, the officials said.
The attackers ran their boat over the floating bodies to make sure
no one was alive, the sources said.
   The two survivors hid under planks floating in the water, and
their boat later drifted to an Esso Oil Co. rig in the South China
Sea off the Trengganu coast of Malaysia, the officials said.
   Workers picked up the two on Monday and sent them to the
Malaysian government hospital in Kuala Trengganu, 180 miles
northeast of Kuala Lumpur. ``This is one of the worst cases of
piracy reported in recent years, and the pirates nowadays kill the
people after plundering the boats so that there would be no
witnesses,'' said a senior refugee official.
   The refugee officials said the two survivors did not give a full
account of their experience. They did not say exactly when the
attack took place or how many pirates took part. There was no word
on the fate of the kidnapped women.
   ``The women are normally raped and either killed and dumped into
the sea or abandoned in remote islands,'' said another refugee
official.
   In January, refugee officials said two Vietnamese women were
raped and dumped on a remote Thai island before arriving at the
camp. The women reported that 26 people in their boat were killed
by Thai pirates late last year.
   The officials said such attacks by Thai pirates had decreased
since the early 1980s when Thai and Malaysian authorities had
stepped up boat patrols. The government reported that in March,
about 2,000 Vietnamese refugees landed on Malaysian shores, almost
double the average for the past few months. There are now about
16,500 Vienamese boat people in Malaysia.
   Malaysia and the nations of the region accept the refugees only
for temporary stay pending permanent settlement in the West.
</TEXT>
