<FIRST>r i PM-ZitaFuneral 1stLd-Writethru a0469 04-01 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zita Funeral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0469,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tens Of Thousands Pay Last Respects To Last Empress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for 8th pvs, ``Royalty, aristocracy...'' to UPDATE
with funeral requiem under way. Pickup 9th graf, ``Visitors came...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people gathered downtown
today to pay final respects to Europe's last empress, Zita, who was
to be buried with all the pageantry of the monarchy that vanished
more than 70 years ago.
   In an outpouring of sentiment for the Hapsburg Empire, up to
2,000 people an hour moved by the velvet-draped coffin in St.
Stephen's Roman Catholic Cathedral containing Zita's body.
   Souvenir sellers outside the cathedral did a brisk trade in
portraits of Zita as a young beauty and in T-shirts that marked the
occasion.
   Austria's largest circulation newspaper, the tabloid Neue Kronen
Zeitung, took up its entire front page with a photograph of
hundreds of mourners waiting to file past the coffin and the simple
headline, ``Farewell to Zita.''
   The headline ran against a background in yellow, the color of
the imperial House of Hapsburg.
   Zita's funeral was planned as the biggest since the Hapsburg
Empire buried Emperor Franz Joseph in 1916.
   Zita died two weeks ago in Switzerland at age 96. After the
collapse of the monarchy in 1918, Zita and her husband, Charles I,
were forced into exile and all titles of nobility were abolished.
   All the Roman Catholic royal familes of Europe sent
representatives to the funeral, but no reigning monarchs attended.
   President Kurt Waldheim was among the mourners in the cathedral.
   At a Mass led by Cardinal Hans Hermann Groer the languages of
the Hapsburg monarchy _ German, Italian, Hungarian, Czech, Croat,
Slovenian and Polish _ sounded in the intercessions read for Zita.
   Visitors came from the far corners of the former monarchy, which
once included Hungary, Yugoslavia, Czechoslovakia and parts of
Italy.
</TEXT>
