<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Scotland-TaxProtest     04-01 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotland-Tax Protest,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Scots Protest New Property Tax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Scots demonstrated today
to protest a new tax that symbolizes the London government many of
them reject.
   Bagpipers led a crowd estimated at 12,000 through the streets to
protest the change, which eliminates local property taxes and
substitutes a flat tax rate for all people 18 and over. The change
took effect today.
   Speakers from opposition parties, churches and other groups
urged people not to pay it _ a response long supported by Scottish
nationalists seeking to make the tax a major issue.
   ``I have got absolutely no intention of paying (the new) tax,''
said Eleanor McLaughlin, Edinburgh's lord provost. She said she
would refuse to pay to join the poor who ``can't afford it.''
   The tax is part of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's crusade
against socialism and high-spending local governments.
   It requires each local authority to calculate its expenses and
set a uniform sum to be paid by every resident 18 and over.
   The sums are expected to average $436 a year per adult, with 80
percent rebates available for those on low incomes.
   The government says it will make local governments more
accountable by forcing municipalities to stop financing social
programs for those who pay little or no tax with money collected
from the middle class.
   But many Scots have said the tax revenue will not be returned to
Scotland.
   Opinion polls show that many believe they will be worse off
because of the new tax, which is due to take effect in England and
Wales in a year.
   The Scottish National Party, which seeks outright independence
for the 5.2 million Scots, was collecting signatures of people
pledging not to pay the tax.
</TEXT>
