<FIRST>r w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0409 04-01 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0409,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Acknowledges Congressional Roadblock Influenced Contra Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: To update with meeting over, SUBS grafs 3-4 bgng ``Bush today
... ''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he would have gotten
nowhere with Congress had he tried to win new military aid for the
Contras, and he denies his diplomatic approach to Nicaragua means
the military efforts had failed.
   ``There was no way, not a snowball's chance in hell, of getting
a dime for lethal aid, military aid, from Congress,'' Bush said
Friday in a question-and-answer session with a group of regional
media representatives. ``And I think anybody who's familiar with
Congress would acknowledge that.''
   Bush today engaged in Latin American diplomacy, meeting with
Venezuela's new president, Carlos Andres Perez, and several top
administration officials.
   The group, including Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, discussed a range of issues of
concern to the Latin world, including the Third World debt crisis
and Central America peace efforts, according to a senior
administration official.
   In the question-and-answer session Friday, rejected a suggestion
that his emphasis on diplomacy in the region amounts to an
admission that President Reagan's policy of military support for
the Contras had failed.
   Bush said military pressure convinced Nicaragua's ruling
Sandinistas to join in peace talks calling for democratic reforms
in their country.
   On other issues, Bush also ruled out any backing away from his
support for expanded oil exploration in Alaska. To turn away from
the oil resources in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, he said,
would be irresponsible, despite the recent environmental disaster
created by the 10-million gallon spill from the Exxon Valdez tanker.
   ``We are becoming increasingly dependent on foreign oil, and
that is not acceptable to any president,'' Bush said. ``We have to
transport oil. What we will do is not go backwards.''
   Bush's comments Friday on the Contras were the first he has made
indicating that the dim prospects for military aid influenced his
decision to pursue a diplomatic solution.
   In a bipartisan package worked out with Congressional leaders,
he is proposing $40 million in nonlethal aid to keep the Contras
intact until the Nicaraguan elections at the beginning of next year.
   ``It's not bad, the policy has been well received,'' he said.
``We are speaking with one voice. We are going to push for
democratization.''
   As to El Salvador's new president, Alfredo Cristiani, the
candidate of the rightist Arena party, Bush said, ``We will treat
the Salvadoran winner on his word, that he wants to continue the
democracy,'' espoused under outgoing Christian Democratic President
Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   He pledged to ``redouble efforts'' for safe transport.
</TEXT>
