<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     04-01 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Die In Unrest In West Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and killed one
Palestinian today in a clash in the village of Bethany, and another
reportedly died of wounds inflicted by Jewish settlers, the army
and Arab hospital officials said.
   The victim in Bethany was shot when a group of Palestinians
stoned an Israeli army jeep patrol and slightly injured two
soldiers, the military said. An army spokesman said the Palestinian
died at an east Jerusalem hospital.
   Arab reporters identified the Palestinian as Akram Mustafa
Mahmoud Yassin, 24, and said he was shot in the heart.
   The army said another Palestinian died of gunshot wounds
suffered Thursday, but could not confirm reports by Arab hospital
officials and Israel radio that he was shot by Jewish settlers.
   Arab reporters identified the victim as Tareq Awad Farah Amir,
23.
   The two deaths would raise the Palestinian death toll to 417
since the uprising against Israeli occupation began in December
1987.
   Eighteen Israelis have also died.
   Arab reporters said Yassin's family took his body from Muqassed
Hospital and buried him in a cemetary near a grotto that was built
in the 4th century A.D. to mark a site believed to be the tomb of
Lazarus. The army imposed a curfew on the village's 4,000 residents
after Yassin's funeral.
   Six Palestinians were also wounded in confrontations with troops.
   They included a 12-year-old Arab from the Gaza Strip who was
shot in the hand; four Arabs were wounded in Gaza City when troops
opened fire to disperse a demonstration in the area's commercial
center; and a 16-year-old boy who was shot and wounded in the West
Bank village of Hajah.
   In the Gaza Strip about 180,000 residents remained under curfew
in six refugee camps and neighborhoods.
   The longest standing curfew is on the Shati refugee camp where
residents have been confined to their homes for 15 days.
