<DOCNO> AP890401-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Najib Bjt   04-01 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Najib, Bjt,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Najib: Firm Talk and a Big, Big Stick</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Earleen Fisher</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>Kabul, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It might be easy for those on the
outside to dismiss President Najib as a hulking, former secret
police chief presiding over a repressive government destined for
defeat.
   But this same man has proved himself to be an eloquent orator, a
shrewd combatant during political infighting, and a politician deft
at appealing to feelings of nationalism.
   The test now at hand is the battle for Jalalabad, where
U.S.-supported Moslem guerrillas have besieged Najib's forces
nearly four weeks.
   Neither side has been able to claim victory. Thousands of people
have surely died, although neither side has sufficient credibility
for its casualty reports to be believed.
   Najib has fired his biggest guns, literally and figuratively.
   The Soviet-supplied Scud-B missiles launched toward Jalalabad
from Kabul several times a day are monster-size weapons, but their
impact may be as much psychological as physical.
   The government makes no effort to conceal its Scuds, trundling
the 36-foot-long missiles through the center of Kabul on open truck
beds in broad daylight. The roar with which they are fired is
unmistakable.
   Their message _ and that of the Air Force MiGs and Sukhois _ is
clear: Najib's weapons outclass any rockets, mortars or shells the
guerrillas can pack across the border from Pakistan.
   Although the Soviet Union withdrew the last of its combat troops
from Afghanistan on Feb. 15, it continues to supply the Kabul
government with Scuds, smaller weapons and food and says it will do
so as long as the United States aids the guerrillas.
   The guerrillas are caught in a dilemma. They are most effective
in hit-and-run attacks, not bogged down in confrontation with a
regular army that outnumbers and outguns them.
   Conversely, regular armies rarely vanquish guerrilla forces
militarily, as the Israelis learned against the Palestine
Liberation Organization in Lebanon and the Indians against Tamil
guerrillas in Sri Lanka.
   The most effective solution is a political one, which is
impossible to achieve unless both sides agree to negotiate. But
guerrilla leaders refuse to talk to Najib and say they will not
give up the fight until his Soviet-style party is removed.
   Najib is giving the political side his best shot.
   ``Fratricide brings nothing but misery and agony,'' the
president said last week in a radio appeal aimed at the guerrillas'
local commanders inside Afghanistan. Referring to them as ``dear
compatriots'' and ``my brothers'' and to their Pakistan-based
political leaders as ``the enemy'' and ``the extremists,'' Najib
offered a cease-fire and local autonomy to commanders who would
stop fighting.
   From guerrilla headquarters in Pakistan came a rejection of
Najib's offer. But the government claims it has opened negotiations
with some local commanders it refused to identify.
   Najib rarely misses an opportunity to accuse Pakistan of
``vicious warmongering,'' of imposing a foreign-inspired war on
Afghans. It is a calculated ploy aimed at the fiercely independent
and tribalistic Afghans' centuries-old antipathy to outsiders.
   There also seems to be a growing feeling in war-weary Kabul that
Najib, although unquestionably an authoritarian leader, is not as
bad as his predecessors in the ruling People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan.
   The Afghan monarchy ended in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was
overthrown by a cousin, Mohammad Daoud. Five years later, the
People's Democratic Party overthrew and assassinated Daoud,
bringing Noor Mohammad Taraki to power.
   Taraki himself was killed in 1979 as party rival Hafizullah Amin
took over. With the Amin regime teetering under guerrilla attacks
and party feuds, the Soviet Union sent troops to Kabul later that
year and Amin was assassinated.
   Amin's successor, Babrak Karmal, in turn was shunted aside by
Najib in 1986.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights monitoring
group, estimated that 35,000 Afghans have been imprisoned or
disappeared _ the majority of them in the pre-Najib early 1980s.
Under Najib, there are still political arrests but the number of
detentions has dropped sharly, according to several foreign
observers who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``Taraki, Amin and Babrak were crazy men. Maybe Najib is not so
bad,'' said one businessman. Others have expressed similar views.
   The party traditionally is divided between the Parcham faction
headed by Najib and the Khalq faction of the late Taraki and Amin.
In October, Najib purged Parchami dissidents and a month later
dispatched the top Khalqi leader, Gen. Mohammad Gulabzoi, to Moscow
as ambassador _ a time-tested Afghan way of getting potential
troublemakers out of the country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Earleen Fisher is The Associated Press bureau
chief of South Asia, based in New Delhi. She has been in Kabul
since March 22.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
