<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Legionnaires'     04-01 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Legionnaires',0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixth Victim Dies in London Outbreak of Legionnaires'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man suffering from Legionnaires' disease has
died, a hospital official said Saturday, bringing to six the death
toll from two separate outbreaks of the illness.
   The Times newspaper said the victim was the first to die from an
outbreak in the Knightsbridge area of London. It said five other
cases had been reported there.
   Another outbreak of the disease in central London killed five
people and sickened 31 others.
   An official at St. Mary's Hospital in west London confirmed that
a man died Friday of the disease, but he refused to give further
details.
   ``I'm not denying it,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``I wouldn't be talking to you if it hadn't
happened, but we have nothing to add.''
   The disease, which causes pneumonia-like symptoms, is believed
to be caused by bacteria found in soil and water supplies such as
air-conditioning ducts or storage tanks.
   A year ago, an outbreak of the disease at the British
Broadcasting Corp. headquarters killed three men. The BBC admitted
breaching health and safety laws and was fined $9,600.
</TEXT>
