<FIRST>r i AM-Ireland-Gorbachev     04-01 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ireland-Gorbachev,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Picks Neutral Ireland for First Western Appearance This
Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For his first appearance in the West
since the Armenian earthquake cut short his U.S. visit in December,
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has chosen a small nation that in some ways
straddles Europe's political, social and military divides.
   The Soviet president's stopover Sunday at Shannon Airport en
route to Cuba and then Britain is the first visit by a Soviet
leader to this 95-percent Roman Catholic country.
   As the most Catholic nation in Europe, Ireland is instinctively
anti-communist, and 85 percent of the population votes for
conservative parties. But it also cherishes the neutrality that
kept it out of World War II and makes it the only member of the
European Economic Community to stay out of the NATO alliance.
   The EEC's drive to harmonize its members' policies leads some
Irish to worry their neutrality is being compromised, and a visit
by the leader of the communist world could help restore the balance.
   For a country of 3.5 million people still undergoing the
transition from a rural to industrial society, even a brief visit
from a Soviet leader is a big prestige boost.
   Irish newspapers Saturday devoted special sections to the visit,
which the Irish Times described as confirmation of Prime Minister
Charles Haughey's ``role as an international statesman.'' The Irish
Independent said the visit was both ``significant and symbolic.''
   Gerald Frost, director of the London Institute for European
Defense and Strategic Studies, observes that an Irish visit is
obligatory for a U.S. president but unusual for a Soviet.
   He said the rare visit will focus attention on ``and probably
facilitate the Gorbachev charm offensive.''
   Gorbachev's six-day trip to communist Cuba and then Britain was
supposed to follow his visit to Washington last December. But he
had to rush home when the Armenian earthquake struck.
   Liam Skelley, deputy head of Aer Rianta, the Irish airports
authority, was mindful of Gorbachev's attempt to curb Soviet vodka
consumption and made tea and coffee available, in addition to Irish
whiskey.
   The visit underlines Irish-Soviet commercial ties, as Shannon's
duty-free stores were open to Gorbachev and his wife Raisa.
   Aer Rianta runs the duty-free shops at Moscow's Sheremetyevo
airport. The symbol of the seven-year joint venture begun last year
is a shamrock on the face of the Kremlin clock.
   In 1980, the Soviet airline Aeroflot began refueling at Shannon
on North American routes. Now 1,500 Aeroflot jets land at Shannon
each year and Skelley and his staff are taking Russian lessons.
   Aer Rianta takes over the Leningrad airport shops this summer
and has a $3.4 million annual contract to paint Aeroflot jets.
   Soviet-Irish trade totaled $62.5 billion last year, running 3-1
in Moscow's favor. But that was down from $75.7 billion in 1987
when Moscow stepped up Irish meat imports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AlamoBattle Bjt   04-01 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alamo Battle, Bjt,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alamo Management Battle Pits Hispanics Against `Daughters of Texas
Republic'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 years ago, legend has it, Alamo
commander William B. Travis drew a line across the grounds of the
old Spanish mission. He asked his men to step over it and defend
the Alamo against thousands of Mexican troops.
   Today, the Daughters of the Republic of Texas, who have cared
for the Alamo for 84 years, are emulating Travis' legendary gesture
as they battle with legislators and Hispanic leaders who want to
wrestle control of the Alamo away from the 6,000-member group.
   Travis lost his battle to Santa Anna in March 1836, but Texas
troops rallied with the cry ``Remember the Alamo!'' and later
defeated Mexican troops to regain the Alamo and win Texas'
independence from Mexico.
   Now, critics of the Daughters of the Republic of Texas say the
mission would be better run by a state agency accountable to the
public, particularly in light of an audit that showed the
Daughters' Alamo chapter with a budget surplus of nearly $2 million.
   ``We aren't hiding anything. Our books are open and we are
complying with the open records and open meetings laws,'' said
Marjorie Hardy, a chapter chairwoman. Tourism officials estimate
chapter members usher close to 10 million visitors a year through
the mission in the heart of downtown.
   Shifting control to the state, Ms. Hardy said, would cost
taxpayers because state workers would be paid for duties that
volunteers now perform. As for the surplus, Ms. Hardy said it was
being saved to build a larger theater in the complex.
   ``We are very proud of what we have done with the Alamo, but we
are not bragging about ourselves. Maybe we should,'' Ms. Hardy said.
   Daughters of the Republic of Texas are descendants of people who
lived in Texas between 1836 and 1845, when it was an independent
republic before becoming part of the United States. The Daughters
received a state charter in 1905 to operate the Alamo.
   The complex includes a chapel with artifacts and flags, a
souvenir shop and research library, a small building where
documentaries are shown and enclosed grounds with several cannons
on display. Admission is free, and operating expenses are covered
by souvenir sales profits. No state money is used.
   Recently, the Daughters asked Attorney General Jim Mattox to
clarify their legal status; he ruled that the group must comply
with the state open records law because it manages a state-owned
site.
   Meanwhile, state Rep. Ron Wilson filed a bill that would
transfer control of the Alamo from the Daughters to the Texas Parks
&amp; Wildlife Department, which operates numerous state parks and
museums.
   ``It's a historical structure, probably the most historical
structure in the state, and for the state not to have control or
management of it is a little absurd,'' he said. A House committee
is slated to have a hearing on the bill later this month.
   Adding fuel to the Alamo controversy is Jose Garcia de Lara,
president of the League of United Latin American Citizens.
   Garcia, who says he is a descendant of Bernardo Gutierrez de
Lara, author of the Republic of Texas declaration of independence,
maintains the Alamo is a symbol of oppression for Hispanics.
   He said the League and the Daughters should work together to see
that Hispanic heroes of the Alamo _ Mexicans who fought alongside
the other Alamo defenders _ are granted the same respect as Travis,
James Bowie and Davy Crockett.
   ``The DRT has a perception that they own the Alamo and because
of that they have managed it and handled it in a way that has
excluded Hispanics from participating in historical activities,''
de Lara said.
   Adela Navarro, 85-year-old descendant of Republic of Texas
statesman Jose Antonio Navarro, also favors state control of the
Alamo, though she herself is a member of a Daughters chapter.
   ``These old girls play dirty politics. The Alamo doesn't belong
to them ...,'' Ms. Navarro said. ``They think they are superior and
they are not.''
   But supporters of the Daughters, including Mayor Henry Cisneros
and state Rep. Orlando Garcia of San Antonio, say the group has
done an admirable job of restoring the Alamo and telling the
history of Texas accurately.
   ``They are blood descendants of the heroes of the Alamo,''
Cisneros said. ``No one else will treat either the building or the
history of the period with the care and reverence they bring to the
task.''
   Garcia, who had asked the Daughters to open their records,
agrees they take care of the Alamo as no one else could and adds,
``the state is not in a position to be assuming new burdens.''
   Pauline Wilson, president of the Daughters' Alamo chapter, said
hard work went into making the Alamo the tourist attraction it is
today.
   ``The older members brought in their husbands, their kids, even
their maids to clean the place out,'' she said. ``Where were all
these people when we were having such a hard time with it?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Defense     04-01 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Defense,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Tower Fight Over, Lawmakers Turn to Juggling Money and Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress, finally freed of the knockdown,
dragged-out fight over the nomination of John Tower as defense
secretary, is focusing on resolving long-overdue problems such as
funding the military in a zero-growth budget and modernizing the
nation's land-based missiles.
   The nearly two-month, bitter debate over Tower, his later
rejection by the Senate and the eventual confirmation of former
Rep. Dick Cheney of Wyoming has delayed Pentagon decisions past set
deadlines.
   In turn, Congress' defense plate remains relatively empty.
   ``The `in box' drives everything,'' Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, said in an
interview last week.
   Among the Pentagon's missed deadlines was a Feb. 15 decision on
funding for the single-warhead Midgetman, the mobile, 10-warhead MX
missile and other land-based modernization programs as well as
budget action due April 3.
   The delay, according to Aspin, will limit Cheney to ``mundane
changes'' as he cuts $6.3 billion from the fiscal 1990 defense
budget originally proposed by former President Reagan.
   ``The changes are not going to be very inspired,'' Aspin said.
``We're facing a brand new era with (Soviet President Mikhail)
Gorbachev ... but I don't think we'll see creative thinking.''
   Aspin praised Cheney's abilities but said time constraints and
the usual delays in Senate confirmation of the defense secretary's
subordinates will limit creativity.
   But Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., a member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said Friday he did not envision any problems
from the lengthy battle over a defense secretary.
   ``It's not an unreasonable delay nor is it as a result going to
create any big problems,'' said Levin, who expects Cheney to make
``better decisions, decisions with more credibility.''
   Cheney is scheduled to meet next week with the Defense Resources
Board on final changes in the defense budget.
   Meanwhile, the Congressional Budget Office said that if Cheney
choses to eliminate some military forces rather than cancel weapons
in response to budget cuts, the result would be massive force
reductions, including six Army divisions and four Navy aircraft
carriers.
   One of the major choices facing the new defense secretary is
deciding on a modernization plan based on the MX, the Midgetman or
a combination of the two.
   Congress decided last year to authorize $850 million in fiscal
1989 to fund the two programs. But until Feb. 15, the Pentagon
could spend no more than $250 million of the total amount on the MX
rail garrison.
   A compromise plan calls for converting the existing 50 MX
missiles from vulnerable silos to railroad cars and building 300 to
500 Midgetman missiles. Aspin said last week that to achieve a
bipartisan consensus in Congress both the MX and Midgetman should
be built.
   But the ranking Republican on the House Armed Services
Committee, Rep. Bill Dickinson of Alabama, criticized the plan,
saying it would place unacceptable limits on defense programs. He
urged his GOP colleagues to vote against the Midgetman unless
Democrats agree to President Bush's request for an increase in
defense spending after fiscal 1990.
   Bush has proposed zero growth in fiscal 1990, 1 percent growth
in fiscal 1991 and fiscal 1992 and 2 percent growth in fiscal 1993.
   Levin said he feared that the combination of MX and Midgetman
will win out.
   ``It's a very expensive thing to do ... I'm afraid that we'll
end up building both. Too often that's the way issues will be
solved,'' he said.
   The Michigan Democrat likened the situation to the decision to
build the B-1 bombers and move forward with the B-2 stealth bomber
after the B-52. Levin favored choosing the B-2 over the B-1.
   ``We've seen huge cost overruns ... as a result of doing
everything instead of making choices,'' Levin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Kidnap     04-01 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Kidnap,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Release of Three Held In Right-Wing Kidnapping Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge, citing a lack of
evidence, has freed two former military officials and an
industrialist jailed three years ago in a highly publicized probe
into right-wing kidnappings.
   Judge Juan Hector Larios on Friday ordered the release of former
Lt. Rodolfo Lopez Sibrian, former Maj. Jose Alfredo Jimenez Moreno
and industrialist Orlando Llovera Ballete.
   Larios also canceled arrest warrants for five other people,
including a former army colonel.
   The judge declared null the acts of a military judge who in 1986
started the proceedings. The case was transferred to civilian court
in 1988 after it was ruled the crimes were not politically
motivated.
   Larrios said statements from witnesses on the kidnappings were
not reliable and that there was insufficient evidence to hold the
men.
   The government alleged that Llovera Ballete and Lopez Sibrian
posed as leftist guerrillas to capture five businessmen in exchange
for about $5 million between 1980 and 1985.
   The two were reported to be close friends of cashiered army Maj.
Roberto d'Aubuisson, founder of the ultra-conservative Republican
Nationalist Alliance. The party's candidate, Alfredo Cristiani, won
the March 16 presidential election.
   D'Aubuisson and his associates have been repeatedly linked to
right-wing death squads that ran rampant in the country in the
early 1980s. D'Aubuisson has denied the charges.
   When police agents captured Llovera Ballete and Lopez Sibrian in
March 1986, it was widely viewed as the start of a case that would
pit the administration of Christian Democrat President Jose
Napoleon Duarte against the conservative sectors of the military.
   Also implicated in the case were Oporto Tereson Roman, Moises
Lopez Arriola and detective Edgardo Sigfredo Linates, who all died
under suspicious circumstances in the following months.
   One was found hanged in his jail cell, another was shot when he
reportedly tried to escape police custody, and the other was gunned
down just outside El Salvador.
   Authorities said the three could have provided important
information in the case.
   Lopez Sibrian also was implicated in the 1981 murders of two
American land advisers _ Mark David Pearlman of Seattle and Michael
P. Hammer of Potomac, Md. _ and a Salvadoran agrarian reform
official.
   The charges against Lopez Sibrian, who was later dismissed from
the army, were dropped because of lack of evidence.
   Pearlman and Hammer were advising the government on a land
reform program that took thousands of acres from wealthy families
and distributed them to peasants.
   Five years later, two former army corporals were convicted in
the case. The U.S. government later maintained that the
``intellectual authors'' of the crime had not been brought to
justice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral Bjt   04-01 1026</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, Bjt,1054</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago's Mayoral Election to Test Mettle of Black Political Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0496 to CORRECT category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six years after the late Harold Washington
changed the course of Chicago politics, the movement that crowned
him mayor has fractured, jeopardizing the brief era of black
leadership he set up on City Hall's fifth floor.
   The likely benefactor of the split is Richard M. Daley, the
white, three-term Cook County prosecutor who unseated Mayor Eugene
Sawyer in the Democratic primary. He heads into Tuesday's election
with polls showing him a strong favorite to occupy the office his
political boss-father held for 21 years.
   But if Daley does in fact defeat third-party candidate Tim
Evans, the lone black in the race, and Republican Edward Vrdolyak,
he will have to work fast to consolidate his power in the nation's
third largest-city. Another election will be held in 1991, when
Washington's second term would have expired.
   ``One of the first things Washington faced _ and handled well _
was sending a message to the voters that didn't back him,'' said
top Daley campaign aide David Axelrod.
   ``He told people in the predominantly white communities that his
administration was going to be even-handed in distributing
services, in appointments and all facets of government ... then
went out and did those things.
   ``Rich Daley the candidate has said many of the same things. And
to do less than that, would not only be morally and ethically
bankrupt,'' Axelrod added, ``it would be politically suicidal.''
   If Daley were to model himself on Washington, he would in a
sense be continuing a tradition. Washington, the city's first black
mayor, learned more than a few of his political tricks from the
elder Daley.
   ``The old man liked to say `Good government is good politics and
good politics is good government,''' recalled Eugene Kennedy, a
Loyola University professor and author of ``Himself,'' a biography
of Richard J. Daley.
   That translated into providing basic services, which Washington
understood, Kennedy said.
   ``I'll never forget him walking in the (white) ethnic
neighborhoods, pointing out broken curbs, busted lights and such,
and telling people, `I'd fix this, but your alderman is blocking
the way,''' Kennedy added. ``Sheer genius.''
   But while Daley would have to reassure blacks that he intended
to treat them fairly, he might also have his hands full keeping his
white constituency happy.
   ``While everybody is wondering whether the black political
movement can be put back together, what's been overlooked is the
high price that loyalty will cost Daley if he wins,'' said Paul
Kleppner, a professor of political science at Northern Illinois
University and the author of ``Chicago Divided: The Making of a
Black Mayor.''
   ``He's got to keep his own troops in line, nurture the split
among blacks, and get some votes in the City Council,'' Kleppner
added. ``And nothing in Chicago politics comes cheap.''
   To be sure, however, the constraints on Tuesday's winner go
beyond the moral, the ethical and even the purely political.
   For one thing, Washington didn't so much dominate his City
Council opposition as outlast it.
   For the first three years of his first term, an anti-Washington
bloc of aldermen thwarted his legislative agenda at nearly every
turn. It was only after a court-ordered remap increased minority
representation in the council that Washington was able to put
together a working majority.
   Either Evans or Daley could command about 20 votes each in the
council, but Daley is more likely to succeed in twisting the arms
of the remaining 10 aldermen.
   Another factor limiting the new mayor will be the paucity of
spoils that can be handed out.
   During the six-term reign of Daley's father, the mayor exercised
control over 40,000 patronage jobs. Federal court rulings since the
1970s have prohibited most political hiring and firing, which means
the next mayor will have fewer than 1,000 jobs to dole out to his
army.
   And the mayor's control over another traditional source of
spoils _ contracts for city services and consultants' fees _ has
been limited by increasing council review powers and a set of
executive guidelines laid down by Washington that guarantee
minorities a representative share.
   But neither promises of fairness nor constraints assuage all the
fears in the black community.
   ``Nothing less than the future of blacks in politics in Chicago
is being threatened. I won't beat around the bush. I want a black
mayor,'' said Lu Palmer, the popular black radio commentator and
political activist.
   After months of avoiding the potentially explosive issue of
race, Evans wandered closer toward the minefield last week in hopes
of energizing black voters in a city where the voting population is
about 48 percent white against 42 percent black.
   ``Richard Daley is getting ready to reopen his father's
plantation,'' Evans, a South Side alderman, told a rally of 12,000
supporters gathered at the University of Illinois-Chicago early
last week.
   Sawyer lost the Feb. 28 primary in large part because many black
supporters of Evans stayed away from the polls. The two men had
become bitter rivals during the council fight to appoint a
temporary successor to Washington.
   As a result, Sawyer drew nearly 130,000 fewer votes in the
city's 19 predominantly black wards than Washington did in the 1987
primary. Sawyer lost to Daley by a margin of just over 100,000
votes.
   The most recent polls show Daley with about 50 percent support
and with a lead of between 14 and 21 points over Evans. Vrdolyak,
whose upstart, write-in candidacy a week before the primary won him
the GOP nomination, is mired at about 5 percent support and not
considered a factor.
   A Daley victory would make Chicago by far the biggest U.S. city
to replace black control of City Hall with white.
   ``To know that Richard Daley would finish out Harold's reign
would be unthinkable,'' said Palmer.
   ``But to know that blacks, on the very anniversary of Dr. King's
assassination, would be so immobilized that we can't get enough
people out on our own day to assure our freedom would show,'' he
added, ``that we get what we deserve.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-01 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bookstore offering a deal on film
processing prompted Tim and Ruby Mixdorf to take in theirs _ all
108 rolls shot over 16 years.
   The Mixdorfs said that through the years they've had just enough
money to buy film, but never enough to pay for processing. They
just kept storing the film in bags in a closet.
   The Oregon State University Bookstore offered a special last
week of $1.99 for any number of exposures on a roll, compared with
the usual $4.99 for 24 exposures or $6.99 for 36.
   When the Mixdorfs took the pictures home, they reviewed nearly
two decades of family life with their teen-agers, Tim, 15, and
Patty, 13. The couple's favorite shots are of the kids as toddlers.
   ``It's really fun seeing them grow up again in the pictures,''
Mrs. Mixdorf said.
   Not all the photos were good, however.
   ``One entire roll of film was of the TV screen,'' Tim said.
``The kids must have gotten a hold of the camera.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Okinawa, a Navy amphibious assault
ship that spent nine months here being overhauled, has been dubbed
the ``Love Boat'' by its sailors after 14 crew members were married
during the vessel's stay.
   ``Yes, Portland's a friendly town,'' said Petty Officer 3rd
Class Timothy Sibbel, a public affairs assistant.
   The warship left Swan Island Ship Repair Yards on Friday for San
Diego. The departure followed shipboard exchanges of plaques and
other mementos between business and civic leaders and ship's
officers. Meanwhile, sailors and their loved ones exchanged kisses
and hugs.
   ``Portland has been very good to us,'' said Capt. Andy J.
Murphy, commanding officer of the Okinawa. ``This community really
put itself out to take care of our crew and their families. Many
will leave their hearts here, and all of us will have some great
memories.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anthony Moore's two-year commercial break
cost his father $1,000.
   The 14-year-old stopped watching television two years ago on a
$500 bet with his father. The initial plan called for the youth to
abstain for one year, but the boy doubled the stakes after winning
that bet to collect another $500.
   Moore, a freshman at Arthur L. Johnson Regional High School,
said the first three tubeless months were the hardest.
   ``At first, nobody thought I'd be able to do it,'' Moore said.
``When people heard I planned on giving up television for two
years, they really began to have their doubts.''
   Before his TV drought ended this weekend, Moore said he had
spent his last two years reading best sellers, playing sports,
lifting weights and going to the movies. But the bet failed in one
of its main objectives.
   ``My grades have actually gone down since I've given up my
television,'' Moore said. ``My dad can't figure it out.''
