<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     04-01 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Rages Despite Cease-Fire Call; One Person Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian forces fired shells at a key power
plant in the Christian heartland Saturday, and artillery and rocket
duels with Christian troops raged on despite a U.N. cease-fire call.
   Police said one person died and 12 were wounded.
   Firefighters controlled a blaze at a fuel depot hit by rockets
in Christian east Beirut last week, and 150,000 evacuees were told
they could return home. But radio stations often interrupted
programming with warnings to residents to stay in bomb shelters.
   Christian sources said the Syrians were planning to escalate the
fighting and had brought in from Damascus new artillery and rocket
batteries. They accused the Syrians of seeking to demolish key
public utilities in the besieged 310-square-mile Christian enclave,
which includes east Beirut and nearby communities northeast of the
city.
   At least 130 people have died and 421 have been wounded in the
latest round of battles in the 14-year civil war.
   The fighting erupted March 8 after Christian army commander Gen.
Michel Aoun tried to blockade militia-run ports that deprive the
government of revenue.
   Aoun also heads a Christian Cabinet, opposed by a rival Moslem
Cabinet backed by Syria.
   Voice of Lebanon, the Christians' main radio station, said
Syrian gunners ``intentionally ignored'' Friday's cease-fire plea
by the U.N. Security Council.
   Voice of the Nation, Moslem west Beirut's most popular station,
said: ``All attempts to arrange a cease-fire have failed. Civilians
have no option but to remain huddled in basements.''
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules,
said Syrian army gunners pounded the Christian heartland with
howitzers and multi-barreled rocket launchers throughout the day.
   He said Aoun's 20,000-strong army retaliated by firing 155mm
howitzer shells into Syrian-policed west Beirut, Druse-held
mountains southeast of the capital and east Lebanon's Bekaa valley.
   A Christian military source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said several Syrian-fired 180mm howitzer shells exploded around the
main power station in the Christian suburb of Zouk, north of Beirut
before dawn.
   A fire at a fuel depot in Beirut's Christian district of Dora
caused by Syrian shelling was ``fizzling out,'' according to Elie
Honein, manager of the Civil Defense department.
   The fire began when a shell hit the depot Monday. A large butane
gas explosion Thursday was set off by another shell.
   Honein said the estimated 150,000 people who evacuated the
densely populated district could return to their homes.
   The U.N. Security Council's president, Ambassador Absa Claude
Diallo of Senegal, made a cease-fire appeal Friday. The Arab League
on Tuesday called for a truce, and a Aoun declared a unilateral
cease-fire declaration on Wednesday.
   The political crisis in Lebanon had been escalating since Sept.
22, when President Amin Gemayel named Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, to
head an interim Cabinet after Parliament failed to elect a new
president.
   Moslems rejected the appointment which violated a national
covenant under which presidents are Maronite Catholics, premiers
Sunnis and house speakers Shiite Moslems.
   They pledged allegiance to Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who now
heads the rival Moslem Cabinet.
</TEXT>
