<FIRST>r i AM-India-Tibet     04-01 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Tibet,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Demonstrators Held Back During Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested about 80 Tibetan youths
who tried to enter the Chinese Embassy during a demonstration
Saturday against Chinese rule in Tibet.
   The demonstrators from the Tibetan Youth Congress marched to New
Delhi from cities across India and gathered in front of the embassy
before trying to scale the main gate and enter the compound.
   Riot police used truncheons to beat back the protesters and
bundled the youths, shouting anti-Chinese slogans, into police vans.
   Earlier Saturday, the group urged Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi to
speak out against ``the ruthless suppression of the Tibetan people
by the Chinese colonial forces.''
   Clashes broke out last month in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa
between Chinese police and Tibetans demanding independence.
According to Chinese officials, 16 people died, but Western
travelers say the death toll was closer to 30.
   The protests began a few days before the 30th anniversary of a
failed uprising in Tibet. The Dalai Lama, spiritual and temporal
ruler of the Tibetans, fled to India on March 31, 1959, three weeks
after the uprising.
   He set up his headquarters and a government-in-exile in the
northern Indian city of Dharmsala, where he supervises the welfare
of about 100,000 other Tibetans in exile in this country.
