<FIRST>r i AM-Yemen-Floods     04-01 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yemen-Floods,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises to 18 in South Yemen Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADEN, South Yemen (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The interior minister said Saturday the
death toll from torrential rains and floods that began last month
has reached 18.
   Saleh al-Seyali also said 40 people have been injured and 2,186
houses and 53 government facilities destroyed.
   The floods inundated 12,634 acres of land and 309 wells and
canals, drowning 2,715 animals, said Al-Seyali, who is in charge of
a special committee overseeing emergency relief work.
   Flash floods, a common occurrence in the southern parts of the
Arabian Peninsula this time of the year, have taken on disaster
proportions in South Yemen since March 19.
   A week ago, reports reaching the capital put the death toll at
13. The floods have been intermittent and there was a fresh
outburst Saturday.
   Helicopters were dropping food and medical supplies to thousands
of people rendered homeless or cut off by blocked roads.
   South Yemen, one of the poorest countries in the Third World,
has launched an international appeal for help. King Fahd of Saudi
Arabia made a personal donation of $8 million.
</TEXT>
