<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-01 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Step Up Attack On Jalalabad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Najib, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas, bolstered by newly
arrived reinforcements, intensified their rocket and artillery
attacks on the government-held city of Jalalabad, the Foreign
Ministry said Saturday.
   Guerrilla bombardments on Thursday and Friday killed 69
civilians and wounded 123, the government said.
   It was one of the highest civilian death tolls reported since
the U.S.-backed guerrillas launched their offensive March 6 in an
effort to oust government troops from the city 75 miles east of
Kabul.
   The siege began less than three weeks after the last Soviet
troops withdrew from Afghanistan after nine years of support for
successive regimes in Kabul.
   Mohammad Nabi Amani, a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry,
reported eight deaths and 27 injuries among government troops and
said 109 opposition fighters were killed and 70 wounded.
   Most of the figures could not be verified, but members of the
Sikh religious minority who arrived in Kabul on Saturday said 22
people were killed Thursday in a Sikh Gurdwara, or temple, in
Jalalabad.
   They said hundreds of people had taken refuge in the Gurdwara as
rocket and shell fire intensified, and they said few people were
venturing outside.
   Amani said 12,000 to 14,000 opposition fighters, including what
he said were ``Pakistani militiamen in Afghan costume,'' were
attacking Jalalabad early in the week and an additional 3,500 men
had joined them by Saturday. He said the new fighters came from
Paktia and Paktika provinces, which are southwest of Nangarhar
province where Jalalabad is located.
   He did not say how many government soldiers were defending the
city.
   The government spokesman said the opposition on Thursday fired
16,000 shells and rockets at Jalalabad and that 2,500 of them fell
in residential areas and destroyed 13 houses.
   On Friday, he said, 900 more rockets and shells hit residential
aras, destroying 43 houses. He did not give a total number of
rounds fired on all targets Friday.
   Amani also read a Foreign Ministry statement accusing the
British foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey Howe, of trying to reimpose
British colonialism on Afghanistan through its support for the
Moslem insurgency.
   Howe met Moslem guerrilla leaders in Pakistan last week.
   In India on Friday, he said only a broad-based Afghan government
will bring peace. He said he found the guerrilla leaders were
willing ``to work for a government that will command a wide
acceptance inside the country.'' But he said such a government must
not be imposed on the Afghan people.
   On Feb. 23, the guerrillas met in Rawalpindi, Pakistan, and
elected a provisional government they hope will replace President
Najib and his Soviet-style People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   Thousands of people have fled Jalalabad since the fighting
started, and the Kabul government says it does not know how many
remain in the city.
   Jalalabad had a population of 200,000 a decade ago, but it
generally was thought to have shrunk to less than half that number
before the guerrilla offensive started. The city is key for the
insurgents, for it would give them a base on Afghan soil to set up
their provisional government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
