<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     04-01 0984</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1019</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The therapist credited by the Beach Boys'
Brian Wilson for his recovery from drug abuse has been banned from
practicing psychology in California for at least two years, state
officials said.
   Eugene Landy surrendered his license last week to the state
Board of Medical Quality Assurance, said Suzanne Taylor, the
board's management services technician.
   Landy, 54, has worked off and on since the mid-1970s with
Wilson, who for years was the creative force behind the Beach Boys.
The group is noted for such hit songs in the 1960s as ``California
Girls'' and ``Surfin' USA.''
   The psychologist, who had been accused of sexual misconduct with
a female patient, gross negligence and other charges brought before
the board, admitted to a single charge of unlawfully prescribing
drugs to Wilson, the Los Angeles Times said in Saturday's editions.
   Landy and Wilson, who are vacationing in Hawaii, could not
immediately be reached for comment.
   Wilson, who was overweight, reclusive and by his own admission
had drug problems for several years, has said Landy's treatments
allowed him to recover his health and return to the recording
studio. His first solo album, released last year, won wide critical
acclaim.
   ``Dr. Landy saved my life,'' Wilson said last June.
   But in their complaint against Landy last year, state
authorities said Landy's relationship with Wilson caused the singer
``severe emotional damage, psychological dependence and financial
exploitation.''
   Landy, who holds a doctorate in psychology from the University
of Oklahoma, calls his methods ``24-hour therapy,'' in which a
therapist attempts to control every aspect of his patient's life.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author William F. Buckley Jr. and fellow voyagers
who paid $39,000 per ticket left Saturday on a supersonic trip
around the world.
   Buckley is leading the 38,343-mile, 22-day trip aboard a British
Airways Concorde jet, with supersonic hops alternating with
stopovers in New York; Acapulco, Mexico; Sri Lanka; Tahiti;
Australia and other points, said airline spokesman Ken Cook.
   Concordes have circled the globe before but not using supersonic
speeds for each leg or for that distance, Cook said. He said the
jet could break more than a dozen speed records, but he did not
name them.
   During the trip, Buckley planned to broadcast his television
show ``Firing Line'' from Cape Town, South Africa, and Sydney,
Australia, Cook said.
   Cook said a Miami-based travel agency, Lorraine Travel Bureau,
chartered the jet for the tour and that all 100 seats for the trip
had been sold out, although not everyone was starting in London.
Most passengers were scheduled to leave from New York.
   The $39,000 ticket price _ per person, double occupancy, as they
say _ included all hotels and meals as well as extras such as a
safari in Africa and cruises in Tahiti, Acapulco and New Zealand.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Ned McWherter, Tennessee's rotund
chief executive who acknowledges a fondness for good home cooking,
says he may be heavy, but he's also healthy.
   Witness his enviable performance on a cholesterol test at the
state Capitol, where hospital workers were checking volunteers as
part of a citywide cholesterol screening campaign.
   McWherter's cholesterol level _ at 130 _ was one of the lowest
checked at the Capitol and well below the ``borderline'' level 200
and the high level of 240, workers said.
   ``I'm healthy as a horse,'' the 250-plus-pound governor said
following Thursday's finger-pricking session. ``I'm just a little
fat and I've lost my hair.''
   McWherter, 58, said he tries to eat a balanced diet including
meat, cabbage and melon.
   Asked to name his favorite food, McWherter laughed and replied,
``Kellogg's cereal,'' an apparent reference to the company's recent
announcement to add a $1 million addition to its Memphis plant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Princess of Wales slipped out of a London
hospital on Saturday, eluding the massed photographers outside, and
hurried home to Kensington Palace to recuperate from the removal of
four wisdom teeth.
   The day after the surgery at the King Edward VII Hospital for
Officers, Diana left by a side exit and sent her dresser Evelyn
Dagley to the front door to play out an elborate charade in front
of the press.
   Miss Dagley went in and out of the hospital laboriously laden
with red suitcases, a cardboard box, a holdall and several
bouquets, while the 27-year-old princess headed for the palace to
nurse her tender jaw in the privacy of her own home.
   The 1{-hour operation to remove the impacted teeth was carried
out under general anesthetic and went without complication, the
hospital said.
   Diana is to resume her duties Tuesday at a charity luncheon.
   Her husband Prince Charles, the heir to the British throne, took
their young sons Prince William and Prince Harry to Balmoral Castle
in Scotland on Friday for a brief holiday during their school
vacation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version also moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Changes in ownership and coaching in
the Dallas Cowboys franchise have met with some resistance from the
public, but Dallas Cowboys quarterback Danny White said he expects
a turnaround.
   ``So far, it's been kind of rocky,'' said White, who spoke to
450 students, faculty and fans at Garden City Community College on
Friday.
   In February, the Cowboys franchise changed hands from Bum Bright
to Arkansas oilman Jerry Jones, and the coaching reins were handed
from legendary Tom Landry to former Miami University coach Jimmy
Johnson.
   ``The people in Dallas don't like being told what they're going
to do,'' he said. ``Here were these two guys coming in, one from
Arkansas and one from Florida, and kicking our good ol' boys out of
town, saying we don't want you anymore after 29 years.''
   White believes the public's opinion of the new ownership will
change. ``When people get to know them, they're going to fall in
love with them. They're great people.''
</TEXT>
