<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Film     04-01 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Film,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film Makers Won't Release Film After Censors Order 48 Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of a South African
anti-war film have decided not to release it in this country after
censors ordered 48 cuts.
   The film, ``The Stick,'' is based loosely on the undeclared
border war fought by South African forces in recent years in
northern Namibia and southern Angola. It has been shown at several
international film festivals and is scheduled to open commercially
in the United States in May.
   Its director, Darrell Roodt, and producer, Anant Singh, said in
a statement Friday they had decided not to release it in South
Africa even though government censors lifted a ban imposed last
year.
   The film makers said the censors ordered 48 cuts, barred anyone
under 21 fron seeing the movie, and ruled that it could only be
shown in theaters with fewer than 200 seats.
   ```The Stick' is a film that should be seen by South Africans,''
Singh said. ``However, the number of excisions ordered would reduce
the film to a simple exploitation picture and destroy the impact
and power that it has now.''
</TEXT>
