<FIRST>r w AM-IMF-WorldBank     04-01 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-World Bank,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Lenders Settle Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Debt Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute between the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank over setting conditions for Third World
loans has been settled, a bank spokesman said Saturday.
   Frank Vogel, a spokesman for the bank, said the dispute was
settled Friday when bank President Barber Conable won approval for
a new agreement from his board of executive directors.
   The board represents the 151 governments that own the bank,
including the United States.
   Conable's agreement was with Michel Camdessus, the Frenchman who
is managing director of the International Monetary Fund, which is
owned by the same 151-member nations.
   Vogel said the accord provides the fund with authority over
``aggregate macroeconomic policy,'' which gives the IMF the leading
role in deciding how loans may affect the economy of a borrowing
country. The agreement also leaves a loophole for the bank to
continue to make certain nondevelopment project loans.
   The agreement seeks to end problems such as the one that cropped
up last October when the two international lending organizations
clashed heads over a loan to Argentina.
</TEXT>
