<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Confession     04-01 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Confession,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Confesses To Wife's Death 12 Years Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTESANO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has confessed to killing his wife
12 years ago in what authorities at the time thought was a traffic
accident.
   A confession by Dennis Potter, 55, of Humptulips was contained
in sworn statements unsealed Friday in Grays Harbor County Superior
Court.
   According to the documents, Potter said he was driven by guilt
to approach county authorities two weeks ago and admit that he
killed his wife in a fight. ``I had no right to take her life,'' he
said.
   ``She was making my life so miserable that I had to get rid of
her,'' Potter told sheriff's deputies in his confession. ``I
decided I was going to enjoy my life a little bit and just lay her
in the ground where she belonged.''
   Potter was arrested Friday for investigation of murder. He was
being held in the county jail pending a decision by county
Prosecutor Steward Menefree on whether to file charges.
   Earlier this week, the county sheriff's office exhumed the body
of Norma L. Potter, who was 40 when she died in 1976. An autopsy
was conducted by the King County medical examiner, and results have
been sent to Grays Harbor authorities.
   In statements to police, Potter described himself as driven by a
rage because ``my wife would do nothing for me, but she expected
everything from me.''
   He said he has now realized his anger ``wasn't a sane way of
thinking.''
   Potter said that on the evening of Nov. 28, 1976, he asked his
wife to accompany him to a tavern in Humptulips, 80 miles southwest
of Seattle, for a drink.
   They went, and each had a drink, but ``she wouldn't talk to
me,'' he said.
   The couple returned home, but Potter said his wife refused to
come inside, ``so I started after her.''
   ``I grabbed her by the coat front and hit her,'' he said. ``As
far as I know, it broke her jaw and knocked her unconscious. She
fell, and I was still in such a rage that I got down alongside of
her. I guess I straddled her and started strangling her.''
   As his wife's breathing became fainter, Potter said he ``got to
feeling sorry for her,'' and tried to revive her with
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
   He decided to take her to a hospital, but changed his mind on
the way.
   ``I thought if I took her to the hospital she could take me to a
court of law to have me put away for being violent,'' he said.
   Instead, he drove down an isolated road, where he decided to
``wreck the car to either kill us both or to see if one of us was
worth saving.''
   He floored the accelerator and crashed the car into a bank of
the twisting road. When Potter came to, he was slumped over the
wheel. He noticed a cut on his forehead, he told deputies.
   His wife had been thrown 10 feet from the car. Potter said he
approached where she lay and heard ``a rasping breath and she quit
breathing.''
   Had she not died at the scene, Potter later told police, he
would have ``taken a tire iron and beat her to death.''
   A court affidavit said investigating officers at the time
accepted Potter's explanation of the accident, and no autopsy was
conducted, even though his wife had indicated to a minister she
feared for her life.
   Menefree, the county prosecutor, said the autopsy confirmed
Potter's description of the fight. He declined to give specifics,
but said autopsy results ``fit into the whole puzzle we're piercing
together.''
</TEXT>
