<FIRST>r i AM-Imam-Funeral     04-01 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Imam-Funeral,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain Imam Of Brussels Mosque Buried In Mecca</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abdullah Ahdal, the Moslem preacher
who was slain in Brussels after distancing himself from death
threats against author Salman Rushdie, was buried Saturday in
Mecca, Islam's holiest city.
   The body of the 36-year-old cleric was flown to Saudi Arabia by
a special jet sent by King Fahd. Abdullah Omar Naseef, the
secretary-general of the Moslem World League, led the funeral
service.
   Ahdal, whose parents live in Mecca, was killed Wednesday at a
mosque in Brussels that is financed by the Moslem World League. He
was considered head of the Moslem community in Brussels, the
Netherlands and Luxembourg.
   Ahdal and his aide, the mosque's Tunisian librarian Salim Behir,
were shot and killed by unidentifed assailants. The aide's body was
flown to Tunisia.
   Belgian authorities are investigating the slayings, but there
had been threats against Ahdal for his moderate views, especially
on the controversial issue of Rushdie's novel, ``The Satanic
Verses.''
   Ahdal supported the Moslem World League, which condemned the
book as blasphemous to Islam but opposed the death threat against
the author by Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. Iranian clerics
have offered a $5.2 million bounty to anyone who kills Rushdie, who
has been in hiding in England since Feb. 14.
   On Friday, Soldiers of Justice, a Moslem fundamentalist group
that is holding a Belgian doctor hostage in Lebanon, claimed it
killed Ahdal and his aide for carrying out ``destructive and
anti-Islamic activities through maintaining contacts with'' Mossad,
Israel's intelligence agency.
   Ahdal is survived by a wife and seven children.
</TEXT>
