<FIRST>r a AM-Official-Bankruptcy     04-01 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Official-Bankruptcy,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Official Files for Bankruptcy to Halt Salary Garnishment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Attorney General Robert Stephan filed
for bankruptcy in federal court, saying he couldn't pay a $200,000
judgment awarded to a former employee who sued him for sexual
harassment.
   He said Friday that garnishment of one-fourth of his $63,000
state salary, combined with interest payments due on the award,
wouldn't leave him enough to live on while he appeals the case.
   A lawsuit filed in 1982 by Marcia Tomson Stingley was settled
out of court, but she later filed another lawsuit for breach of
contract, alleging that Stephan had broken an agreement not to
reveal terms of the settlement.
   A federal court jury ruled in her favor last November and
awarded her $200,000. Garnishment of Stephan's paycheck to begin
paying off the judgment was to begin this month.
   ``Since action has been taken to garnish my wages, declaring
bankruptcy is my only alternative,'' said Stephan, 56.
   Don Krueger, one of Ms. Stingley's attorneys, said he was angry
at Stephan's action.
   ``I think he ought to resign,'' Krueger said. ``He used taxpayer
dollars to defend his lawsuit, and if he had the guts, he would
walk out and resign.''
   Ms. Stingley was fired in 1982 after working three years in the
attorney general's office as a file clerk.
   In her 1982 lawsuit, Ms. Stingley accused Stephan of making
sexual advances on the job. In a sworn deposition, she also accused
him of propositioning her daughter and friends of her daughter.
   Stephan and one of his supporters held a news conference in
October 1985 and disclosed that Ms. Stinley was paid $24,000 to
settle that lawsuit.
   At the time, Stephan, a Republican, was preparing for a bid for
governor in 1986. But in November 1985 he dropped those plans,
saying the criticism and publicity surrounding the harassment case
were unbearable. He also said he regretted having settled the
``unfounded and ridiculous'' lawsuit.
   By filing the Chapter 7 bankruptcy petition Friday, Stephan
stops the garnishment, starting with his next paycheck.
   In the petition, Stephan listed his debts as unknown, and gave
his assets at $70,401, all of which he said are protected from
creditors under Chapter 7.
   Despite his financial troubles, Stephan said, ``I am proud of my
record as attorney general and will continue to carry out my duties
to the very best of my ability.''
   Stephan is serving his third four-year term as attorney general.
He has not indicated whether he intends to seek a fourth term next
year.
</TEXT>
