<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Horseshoes     04-01 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Horseshoes,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader of Western World Dedicates New Horseshoe Pit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House grounds echoed Saturday with
clanking metallic sounds and shouts of ``good shoe'' and ``c'mon
Mr. Smooth.'' It was the president of the United States christening
his new horseshoe pit and showing off his pitching form.
   President Bush was joined by some 150 picnic guests, including
national champion horseshoe pitchers, to inaugurate the 40-foot,
clay pit he had installed next to the White House swimming pool.
   Bush, a horseshoe aficionado, demonstrated his own pitching
style, getting off to a rough start when he played at a secondary
pit dug to handle Saturday's overflow crowd.
   Playing with local sportscasters George Michael and Glenn
Brenner and Washington Redskins tackle Dave Butz, Bush threw a few
marginal shoes, then turned to reporters and joked, ``When you have
guests, one of the rules is to make them feel comfortable and at
home, so I'm trying not to get too close to the stake.''
   ``It stinks,'' was his comment on one of his pitches that went
afar.
   Later, throwing against Gov. Guy Hunt of Alabama, Bush got his
ringer.
   ``Thank you very much,'' he said throwing up his hands and
leaving the pit to others.
   Bush showed a familiarity with horseshoe lingo, shouting such
expressions as ``good shoe'' and ``c'mon Mr. Smooth,'' and ``power
outage'' when someone missed a shot.
   Other governors who tried their hand at the pit were James
Blanchard of Michigan, Carroll Campbell of South Carolina and Kay
Orr of Nebraska.
   The weather was chilly and a brisk wind blew the red-and-white
checked table cloths on the picnic tables set up for hot dogs and
hamburgers.
   The table centerpieces were of daisies and horseshoes. Tuxedoed
waiters served the food and wine. A Navy band played country music.
Bush and first lady Barbara wore matching warm-up jackets.
   Several horseshoe champions were on hand along with a Washington
contingent that included Vice President Dan Quayle, various Cabinet
members and media representatives and friends of the Bushes.
   Bush called for a demonstration by world champion Jim Knisley of
Bremen, Ohio, and the women's champion Diane Lopez of Lompoc,
Calif. They threw a neat series of ringers and near-ringers to
Bush's apparent delight.
   Knisley, who won his second world championship in August in
Pleasanton, Calif., met Bush at the Ohio State Fair last summer
when Bush was campaigning for president.
   Before the picnic, Bush and some of the early guests warmed up
at the pit as the skies clouded over and a chilly breeze picked up.
   Tourists passing by the sidewalk outside the grounds could hear
the sound of clanking horseshoes, but could not see the pit.
Several looked up curiously toward the White House lawn.
</TEXT>
