<FIRST>r a AM-AtollPurchase     04-01 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atoll Purchase,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawaii Pondering $33 Million Purchase of Coral Atoll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE DUNFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Honolulu family is giving state lawmakers
until the end of April to decide whether to buy picturesque Palmyra
Island, an uninhabited coral atoll 960 miles south of here. The
asking price: $33 million.
   Otherwise, the 600 acres of land within the 8,000-acre
reef-protected atoll will go to the highest bidder, preferably one
who is willing to preserve the island's natural beauty, said
Ainsley Fullard-Leo, the youngest of three brothers who own the
island.
   ``We've had it for a number of years now and we're not in a
position to develop it. We're getting on in years and feel it is
time to sell it and move on,'' said Fullard-Leo, 57. ``We're giving
the state the first chance at it.''
   ``I view the purchase with a manifest destiny mentality,'' said
Sen. Russell Blair, who introduced the bill to buy the island. ``It
is something that could be tremendously important for Hawaii's
future generations.''
   People laughed at the Louisiana Purchase and ``Seward's Folly,''
the 1867 purchase of Alaska from Russia for $7 million, Blair said.
   Gov. John Waihee said he is willing to give the purchase ``real
consideration,'' if the Legislature decides to buy it. The bill has
been approved by the state Senate and is pending before the House.
   What makes Palmyra especially attractive is its deep draft
harbor, an airstrip left over from World War II and frequent
rainfall, said Peter Savio, a realtor representing the family.
   In recent years, the island 200 miles north of the equator has
served primarily as a stopping-off place for yachtsmen, he said.
   University of Hawaii scientists view it as ideal for a variety
of oceanographic and marine life research and a possible site for
equatorial space launches. State administration officials say it
could be a vaulable commercial and recreational fishing center.
   Most of the attention from private interests, however, appears
to focus on building an exclusive resort on the flat U-shaped
string of islets that ring two deep lagoons with white sand beaches.
   The family has in recent months had 10 offers in the range of
$30 million from a variety of U.S. and Japanese companies and one
Pacific nation, but most have asked that they not be identified,
Savio said.
   ``We would like to see someone who is ecologically minded take
over and preserve the wildlife and the birds there,'' he said.
   The island, acquired by the Fullard-Leos' parents in 1922 from a
business partner after a fishing enterprise fell on hard times, has
been a financial albatross for the family.
   The family had to sell property in Hawaii to pay for legal
expenses during a seven-year court fight with the U.S. Navy, which
contested the family's title to Palmyra, Fullard-Leo said.
   The family finally won clear title in a 1947 ruling by the U.S.
Supreme Court, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
