<DOCNO> AP890401-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Guyana     04-01 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guyana,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Devalues Currency By 230 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices tripled Saturday for rice,
fuel, cooking gas and airline tickets after Guyana devalued its
currency by 230 percent and doubled interest rates to 35 percent.
   The government increased wages only 20 percent in the move,
which was made to meet International Monetary Fund conditions for
aid.
   Finance Minister Carl Greenidge announced the move during a
budget hearing late Friday to cries of ``shame, shame and
hardship'' from opposition lawmakers.
   ``This is a budget of violence,'' said Cheddi Jagan, leader of
the Marxist opposition People's Progressive Party. The Mirror, an
opposition newspaper, called the devaluation ``murderous.''
   Average daily wages in the South American nation are $2.30,
while a loaf of bread costs $5.
   The Guyana dollar, previously fixed at 10 to the U.S. dollar, is
now worth 33.3 to the dollar. However, by Saturday the U.S. dollar
was fetching 62 Guyana dollars on the black market.
   Though the tough austerity measures were taken to satisfy IMF
conditions for a $1.9 billion aid package, Greenidge said the IMF
has refused to conclude the deal until Guyana raises an additional
$50 million to clear back payments to the fund.
   Greenidge said the government expects to raise the money in two
weeks.
   Guyana, which has had no economic growth in 10 years, is
attempting to secure the IMF package to revamp its stagnant economy.
   This former British colony's main foreign-exchange earning
exports _ bauxite, sugar and rice _ recorded drops in production of
up to 30 percent in 1988.
   For several months the nation of 750,000 has been plagued by
power rationing and outages, food and fuel shortages and spiraling
inflation, causing sporadic strikes and food riots.
   Since the death of Socialist President Forbes Burnham in 1985,
President Desmond Hoyte has moved toward a free-market system,
divesting state enterprises and encouraging foreign capital
investments.
</TEXT>
