<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CanyonRetires 1stLd-Writethru a0554 04-01 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canyon Retires, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Steve Canyon' Gets Air Force Retirement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to recast, SUBS grafs 3-4, `Caniff died ...,
to ADD date of death, end of strip, CORRECTS typo in `prepared.' Pick up
4th graf, `Air Force ...; SUBS grafs 9-11, `Canyon's service ..., to CORRECT
typos in `investigations' and `display.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force Col. Steve Canyon, a comic strip
character who perhaps has done as much for the morale of his
service as anyone, is retiring after a career full of military
honors.
   A service is planned Monday in Columbus on the Ohio State
University campus to honor the comics page hero created by Dayton
native and Ohio State graduate Milton Caniff.
   Caniff died April 3, 1988, at age 81 and the last Steve Canyon
strip appeared in Sunday newspapers June 5.
   Air Force personnel prepared a biography and list of Canyon's
exploits and will present it to the university. An exhibit will be
set up in the journalism school's library, recently dedicated to
Caniff's memory.
   ``Through Steve Canyon, Milt Caniff did a lot to keep up the
spirits of fliers and the Air Force,'' said 1st Lt. Lynn Ellen
Bryant. ``He really became a part of Air Force lore, and people
remember.''
   Ohio State spokesman Leon Rubin said the presentation was the
Air Force's idea. Canyon is said to have attended Ohio State before
joining the Army Air Corps _ the predecessor of the Air Force _ in
1947.
   Ms. Bryant said the Air Force went through all the old Canyon
comic strips, compiling a ``personnel record'' for the character
through his 1988 retirement.
   ``People here (at McGuire Air Force Base in New Jersey) and in
New York have dedicated a lot of time, energy and imagination to
the project,'' Ms. Bryant said. ``We are very happy and honored to
do something that will be seen by others and is going to last.''
   Canyon's service record ``includes decorations, citations,
movement orders for each base, family data, all sorts of good
stuff,'' she said. The Air Force decided that since his record was
so varied, the character should be assigned to the Office of
Special Investigations.
   ``That also allowed us to say certain things were `classified'
and we coudn't discuss them,'' Ms. Bryant said.
   The Air Force will present a modern uniform with Canyon's
insignia, rank and name tag, along with a retirement certificate
for Canyon and his wife, Summer Smith. A display will hold his 13
medals and eight ribbons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan     04-01 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convoy Pulls Out of Khartoum To Begin Massive Relief Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen trucks flying the blue flag of
the United Nations rolled out of the capital Saturday, one of the
first shipments of a $132-million relief operation aimed at feeding
2.5 million people in the south.
   Before the rainy season begins in early May, Operation Lifeline
aims to position at depots more than 100,000 tons of food,
blankets, tents and medical supplies to keep alive those displaced
by famine and civil war.
   Trucks, airplanes, trains and Nile River barges are being
pressed into duty in the project, which for the first time includes
deliveries to villages and areas under control of Christian and
animist rebels fighting the Moslem-dominated government.
   For the first time, both the government and the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army have promised not to attack or otherwise
hinder the relief shipments. Previous efforts were hampered by one
side or the other for political or military reasons.
   In Nairobi, Vincent O'Reilly, the U.N. media spokesman for
Operation Lifeline, said a convoy of five trucks under U.N.
sponsorship carrying 30 tons of food left Kenya on Friday. On
Monday, a 60-truck convoy is scheduled to leave with 1,000 tons of
food and 10 tons of medical supplies, tarpaulins and pallets.
   The drivers who left Khartoum were on a risky 450-mile journey
to the western village of Muglad, just north of the war zone.
Already 12,000 southerners were sheltered in Muglad in mid-March
and hundreds more have been arriving daily.
   The drivers were to to take their vehicles over roads that
hardly deserve the name and nervously close to Kadugli, capital of
Southern Kordofan region, where heavy fighting has been reported in
recent weeks.
   ``If we don't do this, the disaster will be roughly equal to the
disaster of Hiroshima,'' said James A. Grant, the U.N. official
coordinating Operation Lifeline Sudan. ``Or in recent history, it
will be four times larger a disaster than Armenia last fall.''
   Soviet officials estimated 25,000 people died in the massive
earthquake that struck Armenia in December. An estimated 78,000
people died when the United States dropped the atomic bomb on
Hiroshima on Aug. 6, 1945 in its war against Japan, and up to
140,000 died within a few months.
   Nobody knows how many people already have died in Sudan's
6-year-old civil war. Western relief experts put the figure from
1988 alone at 250,000 to 500,000 or more. Some think as many as 2
million have died since the war began in 1983, mostly civilians
driven from their homes who either perished while seeking shelter
or left to starve in refugee camps or besieged towns.
   Grant, special representative of U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar, described the Sudanese operation as ``a race
against time (and) a mission impossible that could be possible with
the cooperation of everybody.''
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's government previously refused to
allow relief agencies' to deal with the rebels.
   Rebel gunners have shot down at least two civilian passenger
planes and one relief plane and have fired on several others,
claiming the government uses civilian and relief aircraft to
transport troops and military supplies. The rebels also have been
blamed for attacks on relief trucks, barges and trains that have
killed dozens of people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
