<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-01 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Colorado, Northeast; Rain in Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   As much as a foot of fresh snow fell on the Colorado Rockies on
Saturday, and about six inches fell in parts of New York state and
Vermont before an Eastern storm began to fizzle.
   A cold front moved across the upper Mississippi Valley and the
central Plains, producing rain from Iowa into western Wisconsin.
Wet snow fell in central and northern Minnesota.
   Light snow tapered off across portions of the central
Appalachians and northern New England after dumping a half foot of
snow across the Adirondacks and the St. Lawrence River valley of
New York state and Vermont.
   Snowfall totals early Saturday included 6 inches at Massena and
Rochester, NY., 5 inches at Buffalo, N.Y., and 3 inches at St.
Albans, Vt.
   Heavy snow fell over the northern and central mountains of
Colorado, where overnight accumulations included 12{ inches at Vail
and 11{ inches at the Beaver Creek ski area.
   Snow and strong winds made driving difficult over mountain
passes. An advisory for snow and blowing snow was posted for the
northern and central mountains of Colorado.
   In the far West, a cold front produced rain over the Pacific
Northwest. Snow advisories were posted for the Cascades of
Washington state and northern Oregon.
   Another cold front moving across Southern California brought
gusty winds to the Mojave Desert.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29
degrees at Caribou and Limestone, Maine, and Saranac Lake, N.Y., to
89 degrees at Thermal, Calif.
   The low in the nation Saturday morning was 8 degrees at
Marquette, Mich.
   The National Weather Service forecast for Sunday called for
scattered rainshowers from western Kansas across much of the middle
Mississippi Valley, southern portions of the upper Great Lakes and
the Ohio Valley to the central Appalachians; rain falling across
much of the northern and central Pacific Coast and the northern and
central Intermountain region; and strong, gusty winds across the
northern and central Rockies.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 30s over northeast
Minnesota, northwest Wisconsin, western upper Michigan and northern
Maine; in the 40s and 50s from the Pacific Northwest across the
northern and central Rockies, North Dakota, much of the upper
Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes to the northern Atlantic
Coast; the 80s over all of Texas except the panhandle to southern
portions of the southern plateau; and in the 90s in parts of the
desert Southwest. The remainder of the nation generally was
expected to have high temperatures in the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
