<FIRST>r a AM-MountainFire 1stLd-Writethru a0510 04-01 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mountain Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Contain Blaze After Several Homes Lost</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with fire growing to 480 acres, containment estimates,
number of firefighters, other details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONE PINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire burning over 480 acres of brush
destroyed a house, a mobile home and two trailers as firefighters
battled flames pushed over rocky terrain by erratic winds Saturday,
authorities said.
   No injuries were reported and there was no estimate on the value
of the loss, said Capt. Will Donaldson of the California Department
of Forestry and Fire Protection.
   The blaze, in the rugged Alabama Hills four miles west of this
small eastern Sierra Nevada town, was 70 percent contained late
Saturday afternoon and was expected to be fully controlled by 6
p.m. Sunday, Donaldson said.
   About 250 firefighters were battling the fire.
   The house was lost when the fire came out of a deep gorge packed
with thick brush. ``It's real, real heavy material at the bottom,''
he said.
   The blaze erupted when smoldering embers from a blaze that had
been controlled several days earlier were whipped up by 60 mph
winds.
   The earlier fire had begun as a controlled burn of a trash pile,
but was whipped out of control by high winds last week, U.S. Forest
Service spokesman Brian Miller said. That fire, which was ignited
March 21, was controlled the following day.
   Steep terrain and winds of about 30 mph hampered firefighters on
Saturday, Miller said. The rugged area's picturesque mountains,
located 175 miles north of Los Angeles, were used in the filming of
many Western movies.
   Firefighters from the Forest Service, Bureau of Land Management,
Los Angeles Department of Water and Power, Inyo and Kern counties
and several area volunteer agencies were on the scene.
</TEXT>
