<FIRST>r a AM-WifeKiller     04-01 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Killer,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feminists, Brooklyn DA Outraged At Light Sentence in Wife Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge faced growing criticism Saturday for
deciding that cultural considerations warranted a light sentence
for a Chinese immigrant who beat his wife to death because she was
unfaithful.
   The New York City chapter of the National Organization for Women
announced that it would complain to the state Commission on
Judicial Conduct in the next two weeks to protest the sentence of
five years probation.
   ``I think the judge has shown both prejudice and bias by giving
the husband probation,'' said Francoise Jacobsohn, the chapter
president. ``It is not acceptable for a man to kill his wife for
any reason.''
   Judge Edward Pincus cited ``cultural aspects'' Thursday in
sentencing Dong Lu Chen, 51, to probation in the slaying of his
wife, Jian Wan Chen, 40.
   The judge noted ``the effect of his wife's behavior on someone
who is essentially born in China, raised in China and took all his
Chinese customs with him to the United States.''
   Attempts to reach Pincus by telephone Saturday were unsuccessful.
   Chen, a garment factory worker, was convicted of second-degree
manslaughter for fatally striking his 99-pound wife in the head
eight times with a hammer on Sept. 7, 1987.
   Pincus, in a five-day non-jury trial in December, acquitted him
of second-degree murder and first-degree manslaughter.
   Chen's lawyer, Stewart Orden, said Chen was unable to form the
intent necessary for second-degree murder or first-degree
manslaughter, partly because of ``the overwhelming shame and
humiliation'' his wife's adultery caused him.
   Brooklyn District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman denounced the
ruling, saying, ``There should be one standard of justice, not one
that depends on the cultural background of a defendant.''
   Orden said he didn't argue at trial that it was acceptable in
China ``to act violently towards an act of indiscretion or
infidelity,'' but referred to his client's cultural background to
show his state of mind at the time of the slaying.
   Trial testimony showed that Chen emigrated from Canton, China in
1986. He left his wife, 16-year-old son and 18-year-old daughter in
Brooklyn when he moved to Maryland to find work as a dishwasher.
   Shortly after he returned to Brooklyn, he confronted his wife in
their bedroom about her infidelity and beat her when she said they
couldn't resume sexual relations, according to Andrea Bernstein, a
spokeswoman for Holtzman.
</TEXT>
