<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     04-01 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Expels Former Provincial Leader, Three Other Officials Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party leadership in
Kosovo province on Saturday expelled an official opposed to
increased Serbian control and three members of the provincial
Politburo resigned.
   The party also rejected the resignation of Rahman Morina, the
Kosovo Communist Party leader who had submitted his resignation
under pressure by striking ethnic Albanian miners.
   In the purge of its ranks following violent demonstrations by
ethnic Albanians Monday and Tuesday that left 24 people dead, the
Kosovo leadership expelled former party chief Azem Vlasi, who is
under arrest, and two other members of the provincial Central
Committee.
   It announced at the end of a 10-hour meeting that three members
of the 13-member Politburo resigned.
   Vlasi, 41, is an ethnic Albanian who headed the provincial party
from 1986 to 1988 and became deeply involved in the conflict
between Serbs, who comprise a minority in Kosovo, and the
Albanians. About 85 percent of Kosovo's 1.9 million people are
ethnic Albanians.
   Vlasi was arrested last month and accused of
counterrevolutionary activity, a charge that carries a possible
death penalty. He was a chief opponent of Serbian Communist Party
leader Slobodan Milosevic.
   Serbia is Yugoslavia's largest republic and Kosovo is a Serbian
province that had a high degree of automoy. Constitutional changes
that took effect Tuesday gave Serbia more control over Kosovo's
judiciary, schools and police.
   Serbian leaders said the changes were needed to protect the Serb
minority from harassment by the Albanians.
   Thousands of ethnic Albanians took to the streets to protest and
officials reported 24 people, including two policemen, were killed
and more than 200 were injured in fighting early last week.
   Saturday was the anniversary of riots by ethnic Albanians in
1981 that left at least nine people dead. Authorities feared
renewed violence Saturday but reported it was quiet as police
forces patrolled the province.
   Saturday's party meeting was held amid tight security in the
provincial capital of Pristina.
   The leaders rejected the resignation by Morina who agreed to
step down after an eight-day sit-in by 1,300 ethnic Albanian miners
in the Stari Trg lead and zinc mine in February.
   The miners refused to leave the pit until Morina, an ethnic
Albanian, and two other party officials resigned. The miners said
Morina gave in to Serbian demands to change the constitution.
</TEXT>
