<FIRST>r a AM-SigmaDeltaChiAwards     04-01 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sigma Delta Chi Awards,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalism Society Announces Distinguished Service Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of reports in The Christian Science
Monitor about chemical and biological weapons was among the winners
announced Saturday in the 1988 Sigma Delta Chi Distinguished
Service Awards for excellence in journalism.
   The Society of Professional Journalists, which bestows the
awards, cited the Monitor's Gary Thatcher for general reporting by
a newspaper with a circulation of more than 100,000.
   Peggy O'Crowley of The News Tribune in Woodbridge and Perth
Amboy, N.J., was the winner in the category of newspapers with a
circulation under 100,000 for a series on the Perth Amboy school
system.
   The Denver Post's editorial page editor Chuck Green, assistant
editorial page editor Fred Brown and editorial writer Jack Cox won
in the editorial writing category for a series of editorials on a
Colorado district attorney who failed to bring charges in a child
sexual abuse case.
   James O'Shea of the Chicago Tribune won for Washington
correspondence for his work on the savings and loan crisis.
   Washington Post correspondent Douglas Farah won in foreign
correspondence for his coverage of death squads in El Salvador.
   Joe Cavaretta of The Albuquerque Tribune won for news
photography for his photos accompanying ``Gallup: A town under the
influence.'' The series explored the problems of alcoholism among
Indians who live near Gallup, N.M.
   The award for editoral cartooning went to Jack Higgins of the
Chicago Sun-Times for his cartoon, ``Mind if I play through?'' The
cartoon shows a young Dan Quayle playing golf while a naked
Vietnamese girl flees a napalm attack in 1968.
   Higgins was awarded the Pulitzer Prize last week for his
cartoons.
   Two other Pulitzer winners _ The Philadelphia Inquirer and the
Anchorage (Alaska) Daily News _ also received Sigma Delta Chi
awards for the same articles that were cited by the Pulitzer board.
   The Inquirer won a public service award from the journalism
society for investigating hundreds of special tax breaks included
in the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
   The Daily News received a public service award for its
investigation of the impact of alcohol on Native Americans in
Alaska.
   The awards have been presented annually since 1940, and this
year will be presented to the winners at a banquet in Nashville,
Tenn., on May 6.
   Also given Distiguished Service Awards by the society were:
   _ Jacqueline E. Sharkey, magazine reporting, for ``The
Contra-Drug Trade Off,'' which appeared in Common Cause.
   _ Atlanta Magazine, public service in magazine journalism, for
``High School,'' which investigated ways some teens succeed and
others fail in high school.
   _ KRRI-FM of Boulder City, Nev., radio spot-news reporting, for
reporting on an explosion at the Pacific Engineering Co. rocket
fuel plant outside Las Vegas.
   _ KNX-AM of Los Angeles, public service, for its reporting on
the California automobile insurance crisis and the various ballot
initiatives to solve it.
   _ G. Donald Gale of radio station KSL in Salt Lake City, radio
editorializing, for commentaries opposing three initiatives on the
Utah ballot.
   _ WTHR-TV of Indianapolis, television spot-news reporting, for
coverage of the Murat Shrine Club fire.
   _ ABC News, public service, for its ``Nightline in the Holy
Land: Town Meeting.''
   _ WBRZ-TV of Baton Rouge, La., public service, for its coverage
of evangelist Jimmy Swaggart.
   _ KGTV San Diego editorial director John Beatty, news director
Paul Sands and general manager Ed Quinn, television editorializing,
for a series of editorials on issues ranging from homelessness to
the mayor's leadership.
   _ Thomas B. Littlewood, professor of journalism at the
University of Illinois, for research about journalism in exploring
a $9.2 million libel judgment against an Illinois newspaper for a
story it did not print.
   _ New Jersey Network in Newark, bicentennial broadcast award,
for ``The First Amendment: a 200-year test.''
</TEXT>
