<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     04-01 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Offers Peace Package to Tamil and Sinhalese Radicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa on
Saturday appealed to Sinhalese militants and Tamil rebels to
negotiate an end to more than six years of ethnic violence, and
said Indian troops would be sent home.
   ``I personally guarantee your safety,'' Premadasa said at a
public meeting in the village of Girandurukotte, northeast of
Colombo. ``Let us forget the past and start a new era. I don't deny
the wrong done to you in the past.''
   His speech was broadcast over state-run radio.
   Premadasa promised to scrap the controversial India-Sri Lanka
peace accord under which 40,000 Indian soldiers have been sent to
the Indian Ocean island nation to put down the rebellion by Tamil
militants.
   He said Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi had agreed to remove
the troops, and that the accord would be replaced by a peace treaty
between the two countries.
   Premadasa also offered radicals seats in Parliament. He promised
to do away with strict anti-terrorism laws and outlaw vigilante
groups that have been blamed for the killings of Sinhalese
suspected of being militants.
   He said his proposals were backed by all major opposition
parties in the country.
   ``Leaders of all opposition political parties will appoint their
representatives to monitor the security of everybody ... who wants
to give up violence,'' Premadasa said.
   There were no immediate comment from either the Tamil rebel
groups or the Sinhalese militants.
   An official of the opposition Sri Lanka Freedom Party, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said the proposals ``seemed impressive,
sincere and may work. But let us see.''
   Premadasa said 29 members in the 225-seat Parliament would be
moved out to make way for the radicals. ``I am prepared to do this
to allow your voice to be heard, your problems to be sorted out,''
he said.
   The 29 members, who include 15 from Premadasa's United National
Party, were nominated to Parliament in a system under which parties
got bonus seats on the basis of votes in the Feb. 15 general
elections.
   Sri Lanka, once known only for its tranquil beach resorts,
gemstones and tea, has been torn by ethnic tensions since 1983,
when Tamil militants launched a separatist war claiming
discrimination by the Sinhalese majority.
   Sinhalese militants launched their campaign after they accused
the government of being too generous in concessions to the Tamils.
   More than 12,500 people have been killed in ethnic violence.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese, who control the army and the government, make up 75
percent.
</TEXT>
