<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Korn     04-01 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Korn,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Distance Telephone Pioneer Dies at 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Franklin A. Korn, a Bell Telephone
Laboratories researcher who helped create touch-tone telephones and
the direct-dial long-distance system, has died at the age of 83.
   Korn, who retired from Bell Labs in 1970 after 50 years with the
company, died at home Friday of kidney failure, said his daughter,
Barbara Trimmer Hudyk.
   Korn was director of telephone laboratories at the former
Western Electric plant here now owned by AT&amp;T. He was credited with
developing a nationwide direct-dial military telephone network
during World War II, and with the development of touch-tone dialing.
   He also co-invented the switching system used by telephone
companies until the mid-1970s, when electronic switching was
introduced, according to Harold Heckendorn, retired engineering
manager of the Western Electric plant.
   Korn held about 15 telephone-related patents, said his grandson,
David Trimmer, and was named a fellow of the Institute of
Electronic and Electrical Engineers, the highest honor bestowed by
the professional organization.
   He is survived by his wife, a daughter, two grandchildren and a
great-grandchild, family members said.
</TEXT>
