<FIRST>r r AM-Cuba-Asylum     04-01 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Asylum,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Cubans End Nine Years Of Asylum in Peruvian Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Cubans who gained asylum in the Peruvian
Embassy nine years ago have returned home after receiving
government assurances they will be allowed to leave the country,
diplomatic sources said Saturday.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Felino
Ramirez Batista, 58, and Eduardo Herrera Dia, 39, left the embassy
Friday after accepting a promise by the Cuban government that they
will be permitted to emigrate within six months.
   Their departure brought to an end a series of events that began
in the spring of 1980 and culminated in the Mariel boat lift, when
125,000 Cubans fled to the United States between April and
September.
   The two were among some 10,000 Cubans who entered the Peruvian
Embassy in early April 1980 hoping to leave their island homeland
and its communist government.
   The people packed into the embassy after Cuba removed its
security guards from outside the complex because of a dispute with
Peru.
   Virtually all of the Cubans in the Peruvian Embassy were allowed
to leave the country. President Fidel Castro's government opened
the port of Mariel to Cubans wishing to emigrate to the United
States and the massive exodus began.
   But Ramirez and Herrera refused to leave the embassy, fearing
they would be arrested.
   A companion, Pedro Betancourt, 30, left the embassy last October
and departed for Canada two weeks ago, and that apparently gave the
two holdouts confidence they could leave the grounds safely and
then emigrate, a Peruvian consular official said.
   In an effort to break the deadlock over Ramirez and Herrera, the
Cuban and Peruvian governments signed an agreement last May under
which Cuba promised to allow them to emigrate within six months of
their departure from the embassy.
   But the two questioned Cuba's assurances and they staged a
hunger strike during a visit in September by officials of the U.N.
Human Rights Commission.
   The Peruvian Embassy provided the two Cubans with food and
clothing during their stay. The two spent much of their time in the
embassy working on a vegetable garden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
