<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Papandreou     04-01 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Papandreou,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Premier Launches Election Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VOLOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou on Saturday
launched his election campaign by defending his government's
handling of a multimillion-dollar banking scandal.
   Speaking before tens of thousands of his supporters in this
central port city, Papandreou said he was confident his ruling
Panhellenic Socialist Movement would be re-elected to another
four-year term in the June 18 elections.
   ``The government and I personally set into motion all the
procedures provided by the constitution to clear up the scandal,''
Papandreou said.
   His socialist government has been accused of involvement in the
financial scandal surrounding fugitive Greek banker George
Koskotas, jailed in the United States pending an extradition
hearing.
   It was Papandreou's first appearance at a mass public rally
since his return from open-heart surgery in London in October.
   He was first elected to office in 1981, and again in 1985.
   The main conservative opposition New Democracy party said in a
statement that Papandreou ``tried with his April Fool's Day speech
to present a restored picture'' of himself and his party.
   ``Nothing he said deserves special comment,'' the statement said.
   The banking scandal and the 70-year-old premier's open affair
with a 34-year-old former airline stewardess have hurt his standing
considerably among voters, according to recent public opinion polls.
   Papandreou has dismissed the scandal as a ``foreign and domestic
plot'' to overthrow his government.
   Koskotas, former chairman of the Bank of Crete, fled Greece last
November after being indicted in a $200 million fraud, forgery and
embezzlement scandal. He was arrested in the United States.
   In interviews from jail in Salem, Mass., he has claimed that
Papandreou and other senior government officials received millions
of dollars in payoffs and authorized the looting of his bank.
