<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--GulfFrigate     04-01 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gulf Frigate,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Samuel B. Roberts Returns to the Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy frigate Samuel B. Roberts,
severely damaged by a mine while on patrol in the Persian Gulf
nearly a year ago, returned to the water in Portland harbor
Saturday.
   The Roberts has been drydocked at the Bath Iron Works overhaul
yard in Portland since December while crews repaired the vessel's
midsection and installed a new main engine room.
   The 3,600-ton guided missile frigate, which was built by BIW,
struck a mine on April 14, 1988 after completing a convoy operation
for a reflagged Kuwaiti tanker.
   Company spokesman Jim McGregor said repairs were completed about
a week ahead of schedule. The Roberts is scheduled to rejoin the
Navy fleet late this year.
</TEXT>
