<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 2136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala-US     04-01 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala-US,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Helicopters Delivered Supplies To Isolated Guatemalans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy said Saturday that two
U.S. military helicopters delivered food, medical supplies and
doctors to Guatemalans living in an isolated mountain area.
   Embassy spokesman John Treacy told The Associated Press that the
Guatemalan military asked for the helicopters to transport supplies
to more than 1,500 people in an area in Quiche province 160 miles
north of Guatemala City.
   Thousands of people remain in the isolated area where they fled
in the early 1980s to avoid fighting between security forces and
rebels. The Guatemalan military says leftist guerrillas still
operate in the area.
   Treacy said the helicopters, based in Honduras, arrived in
Guatamala March 26 and returned to Honduras three days later after
carrying food, medicine, construction material and medical
personnel to Quiche.
   The United States agreed to the Guatemalan request because there
are no roads to the area and the Guatemalan army did not have the
helicopters to move the needed supplies, he said.
</TEXT>
