<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MedicarePenalties     04-01 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare Penalties,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Recommends Higher Medicare Penalties for Poor Quality Health
Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government study recommends a new penalty
structure for doctors who provide poor quality care to Medicare
patients.
   The General Accounting Office said the current system of
limiting penalties to the amount of the cost to Medicaid sometimes
results in penalties that are disproportionately low compared with
the nature of the offense.
   For example, in one case the report said a doctor endangered a
cardiac patient by releasing her from the hospital although she
showed symptoms of a second heart attack. Because there was no
additional cost to the Medicare program stemming from the doctor's
negligence, no financial penalty could be imposed, GAO said.
   GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, recommended that the
cost-based limit be replaced by a fixed upper limit on the size of
monetary penalties. It did not recommend where the limit should be
set.
   The GAO said that in July 1987, the inspector general of the
Department of Health and Human Services advised peer review
organizations not to recommend financial penalties unless the
Medicare provider had displayed a pattern of poor care and a
significant amount of Medicare payment to the doctor was involved.
   The inspector general has since decided to drop that criteria,
the GAO said, but as of February there had been no formal
notification to halt the July 1987 criteria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
