<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 2156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-West-EasternEurope     04-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-West-Eastern Europe,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says U.S.-Soviet Talks on Eastern Europe Would Be Inappropriate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A White House official said Saturday it
would be ``highly inappropriate'' for the United States to hold
discussions with the Soviet Union on a framework for change in
Eastern Europe.
   ``I am not enthusiastic about that approach,'' Robert M. Gates,
deputy assistant to President Bush for national security affairs,
told an international conference,
   Manfred Woerner, secretary-general of the 16-nation North
Atlantic Treaty Organization, expressed reservations about trying
``to control the course of events'' in Soviet-dominated Eastern
Europe.
   They spoke at the Quadrangular Forum sponsored by the
Brussels-based Center for European Policy Studies and the Center
for Strategic and International Studies in Washington.
   Their remarks were in response to recent reports that the Bush
administration is studying a proposal by former Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger on Eastern Europe.
   According to those reports the proposal would be for the Kremlin
to ease its political and military grip on Eastern Europe in
exchange for Western assuances not to take advantage of the
situation to threaten Soviet security.
   Gates, asked about the proposal, said the Bush administration is
still conducting foreign policy reviews.
   He added he believed that ``any discussion with the Soviet Union
over Eastern Europe in a bilateral context would be highly
inappropriate.''
   It also would not be appropriate from the standpoint of
America's allies or Eastern Europeans, he said.
   Woerner said the West should discuss the future of Eastern
Europe with Soviet officials and added: .
   ``We will continue to respect legitimate Soviet security
interests. But we cannot, and should not, try to patronize
developments in the East.''
   Gates urged a cautious approach in dealing with the changes
under way in the Soviet Union under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``We cannot _ and should not _ close our eyes to momentous
developments in the U.S.S.R. But we should not make concessions
based on hope and popular enthusiasms in the West or attractive
personalities in the U.S.S.R.,'' he said.
</TEXT>
