<DOCNO> AP890401-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-IsraelPoll     04-01 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel Poll,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Majority Of Israeli Jews Say Talks With PLO Inevitable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost two-thirds of Israeli Jews say talks with
the Palestine Liberation Organization are inevitable in the next
five years, but an overwhelming majority oppose beginning peace
negotiations now, The New York Times reported in its Sunday
editions.
   According to a poll conducted in Israel March 23-28 for the
Times, only 18 percent said negotiations should now be started on
the basis of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's recent statement that he
recognized Israel's right to exist in the Middle East.
   But 62 percent said such talks are inevitable in the next five
years.
   And 58 percent _ the highest number since the question was first
asked almost six years ago _ say they would be willing to open
talks with the PLO if it ``officially recognizes Israel and ceases
terrorist activities.
   Regardless of whether they approved of the idea, 44 percent said
they thought a Palestinian state in part or all of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip was inevitable in the next 10 or 20 years.
   Only 37 percent said they thought it was possible for Israel to
live in peace with a Palestinian state in those territories. More
than half, 54 percent, however, said Israel should be willing to
give up some territory in exchange for ``suitable guarantees,'' up
from 41 percent two years ago.
   Nearly three-fourths, 72 percent, said they saw no contradiction
between the army's handling of the Palestinian uprising in the
occupied territories, which emphasizes the use of force, and ``the
nation's democratic values.''
   The house-to-house survey of 1,096 Israeli Jews has a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
