<DOCNO> AP890401-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 2213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Ariane     04-01 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Ariane,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ariane Sends Satellite Into Orbit After One-Day Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe's Ariane-2 rocket, after a
24-hour delay, lifted a communications satellite for Finland,
Sweden and Norway into Earth orbit Saturday night.
   The rocket was launched from the European Space Agency center at
Kourou on the northern coast of South America.
   Arianespace officials announced 20 minutes after the launch that
the mission was completed successfully, with the TELE-X satellite
placed in orbit.
   The launch had been scheduled for Friday night but was postponed
by a last-minute malfunction of the ground computer system.
   The satellite, a program of the three Nordic governments, is to
provide direct television broadcasts to home satellite dishes and
business communications between ground terminals.
   Swedish Space Corp. is overseeing the program. The satellite,
owned by Nordic Satellite Co., is to serve up to 5,000 business
users.
   Officials said the television signals will be powerful enough to
be received by an antenna just 12 inches in diameter. Programming
has not yet been lined up for the broadcasts.
   Arianespace is in charge of production, marketing and launches
of the Ariane rockets developed by the 13-nation European Space
Agency. Norway and Sweden are among the member states while Finland
is an associate member state.
   Arianespace carried out seven missions last year as well as
successful launches on Jan. 26 and March 6 this year.
   There are 33 satellites on the Arianespace order book for future
launches. The European consortium has captured about half of the
world market for commercial satellite launches.
</TEXT>
