<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--SavannahRiver     04-01 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Savannah River,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savannah River Plant Gets New Operator, New Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse took over management of the
troubled Savannah River Plant on Saturday and immediately renamed
the nuclear weapons facility the Savannah River Site.
   Jack Herrmann, a Westinghouse spokesman, said the new name is
``basically symbolic.''
   Under the former operator, DuPont Corp., the operations,
laboratory and construction departments all reported to different
managers. The name Savannah River Plant was used by the company as
a reference to operations only.
   Under Westinghouse, those departments all report to the same man
_ James Moore, president of Westinghouse Savannah River Co. ``We're
just trying to develop better cohesion,'' Hermann said.
   The three reactors at the plant, which makes nuclear weapons
grade plutonium and tritium, have been idle for nearly a year
because of safety and structural problems.
</TEXT>
