<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     04-01 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodriguez Nominated for President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who ousted
dictator Alfredo Stroessner in a coup two months ago, was nominated
for president Saturday by the governing Colorado Party.
   Elections are set for May 1.
   Colorado Party President Juan Ramon Chaves had endorsed
Rodriguez several weeks ago and his nomination by more than 1,000
delegates at the party convention was assured.
   Rodriguez, 65, ended Gen. Stroessner's 34-year rule with the
Feb. 3 coup and Stroessner is now living in exile in Brazil.
   The Colorado Party has been in power since 1947 and claims 1.4
million members among Paraguay's population of less than 4 million.
Its endorsement makes Rodriguez the front-runner and opposition
candidates acknowledge they have little chance to defeat him.
   The Colorados also are almost certain to control Congress. Under
the law, the party that wins a majority of votes automatically
receives two-thirds of the 36 seats in the Senate and the 72 seats
in the Chamber of Deputies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
