<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Seek Tipster In Eighth Highway Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities appealed to an anonymous
tipster Saturday to step forward with information about the latest
of eight women's bodies to be found along local highways.
   The unidentified informant wrote a letter to District Attorney
Ronald Pina about two weeks ago saying a woman's body could be
found along state Route 88.
   Authorities searched without finding the body, but two boys
found the skeletal remains of a woman on Friday about 25 feet off
Route 88 in Westport, just south of where investigators had been
looking.
   Officials have been trying since last fall to solve the mystery
surrounding womens' bodies that have been found since July along
three local highways. The seventh body was discovered Tuesday off
Route 140 in Freetown.
   Investigators say they have established a link between the seven
identified victims and prostitution or drugs in New Bedford's Weld
Square area.
   Pina said the most recent victim, like the others, was
apparently a young woman. She remained unidentified after an
autopsy Saturday.
   Jim Martin, a spokesman for Pina, said the remains would be
given to a forensic specialist who would examine dental records and
perform further tests early next week.
   Pina said the tipster's letter said the author would consider
coming forward if the body was found. Martin said authorities were
strongly urging the informant to do so.
   Investigators have said they have four suspects in the case, but
so far no arrests have been made.
