<FIRST>u a AM-StudioSale 1stLd-Writethru a0600 04-01 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Studio Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed UA-MGM Deal Latest And Biggest In Foreign Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Under the ..., with 5 grafs to UPDATE with reported
MCA deal, chairman's no-comment; Qintex is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $1 billion sale of United Artists to an
Australian company was the biggest in a series of moves by foreign
companies to gobble up successful American entertainment firms.
   United Artists, which produced the Oscar-winning ``Rain Man,''
joined the legion of foreign-owned companies that now includes CBS
Records, MTM Enterprises, Atlantic Entertainment, Cannon Group and
New World Pictures.
   In another reported Hollywood deal-in-the-making, MCA President
Sidney Sheinberg declined to comment Saturday on a report that
Japan's Sony Corp. was negotiating to acquire his entertainment
conglomerate, which owns Universal Studios.
   ``I'm not talking about anything to do with Sony,'' Sheinberg
said Saturday night at the American Cinamatheque's annual benefit,
The Moving Picture Ball. ``We're not commenting.''
   KNX-AM News Radio, a CBS affiliate, reported that executives of
MCA and Sony met Friday at the New Otani Hotel in Los Angeles to
wrap up a deal in which the Japanese electronics firm would acquire
MCA.
   The station, without revealing its source, reported that no
dollar amount was disclosed, but that MCA is worth an estimated
$2.5 billion. The station said the deal would be formally announced
Monday.
   Under the United Artists deal announced Friday, Australia's
Qintex Group has agreed to purchase all outstanding stock of UA's
parent company, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer_United Artists.
   Qintex, best known in the United States as one of the makers of
the CBS miniseries ``Lonesome Dove,'' also would get the United
Artists moviemaking group and its film library.
   But MGM-UA's major stockholder, Kirk Kerkorian, would retain
control of the MGM name and TV and movie studios, as well as 34 MGM
movies, including ``Moonstruck'' and ``A Fish Called Wanda.''
   The MGM-UA deal, if approved, would mark the first time a major
Hollywood studio passed into predominantly foreign ownership.
Australian Rupert Murdoch became a U.S. citizen before buying a
controlling interest in 20th Century Fox in 1985.
   But MGM-UA would not be the only entertainment company to be
bought by a foreign company.
   MTM Enterprises was acquired for $310 million in July by British
broadcaster Television South PLC and Atlantic Entertainment went to
Australian businessman Alan Saffron in December.
   Italian producers Giancarlo Parretti and Florio Fiorini also
have been picking up some of Hollywood, including the small studios
Cannon Group and New World Pictures.
   The UA-MGM deal, and the foreign invasion in general, have
sparked the concern of at least one American network official, who
questioned the fairness of federal regulations that forbid the
networks from making the same kind of deals open to overseas firms.
   Rules drafted in the early 1970s, when the networks were the
only television game in town and cable and pay-for-view were still
about a decade away, prohibit the networks from going into the
production business.
   ``Our view is that it is increasingly ironic and shortsighted to
have policies on the books which allow foreign interests to
dominate entertainment production while America's most logical
competitors, the networks, continue to be shut out,'' said Joe
Rutledge, director of corporate communications for NBC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890401-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 2357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam     04-01 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam's Communist Party Will Tolerate No Challenge To Its Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's Communist Party leadership
has reaffirmed a need for reform but declared it will not tolerate
any challenges to its authority or basic principles.
   Comprehensive reform requires efforts to ``broaden socialist
democracy,'' but the party must tread carefully, party chief Nguyen
Van Linh told a March 20-29 conference of the Central Committee.
   Radio Hanoi, in a report Saturday on the plenum , quoted Linh as
saying:
   ``All attempts aimed at weakening or nullifying the party's
leadership and creating political counterweights to the party in
society must definitely be checked.''
   ``We do not allow those who take advantage of democracy and
openness to attack the party and its leadership,'' he said. ``It is
necessary to clearly distinguish constructive criticism from
mud-slinging and instigating attempts aimed at lowering the
prestige of the party and state.''
   The broadcast, monitored in Bangkok, reported Linh said the
leadership advocates enhancing the roles of state-supervised mass
organizations and of elected organs like the National Assembly.
   ``We advocate broadening democracy and reaching a consensus
through debate, but we do not tolerate pluralism,'' he declared.
   Linh's speech closed the Central Committee's sixth plenum, held
to review reforms endorsed at the national party congress in 1986.
   Linh became party chief at the congress and three leaders
identified with old policies retired.
   But Western analysts said party conservatives remain concerned
that reforms may erode the dominant position of the party that
achieved power after decades of fighting the French, Japanese and
Americans and South Vietnamese anti-communists.
   Radio Hanoi reported Linh told the Central Committee that the
party must avoid prejudice against private enterprises but also
must not favor them ``without realizing their limits and
spontaneity, which leads to lack of close management control.''
   Without giving details, the broadcast reported Linh said the
state will promulgate laws stipulating which industries cannot be
run by private individuals.
   Linh said Vietnam's development requires increased commercial
ties with non-socialist nations but that while ties were being
expanded the party must watch out for ``negative influences.''
   ``Once our door is open, not only will the pure and healthy air
come in but dust, flies, and mosquitos also will follow,'' he said.
   A Central Committee communique, also carried by Radio Hanoi,
said reforms were designed not to change the goal of socialism but
to achieve it more quickly.
   It said the reform of the political system ``is meant to
strengthen the party's role of leadership and the state's
managerial efficacy and the people's right to mastery.''
   The communique blamed the uneven pace of reform on the ``many
shortcomings'' of the party leadership and the state, with
authorities slow to implement party resolutions and to make needed
changes in the party and state structures.
   In his comments on the economy, Linh blamed inflation on the low
output of state-run enterprises and the government's policy of
subsidizing key areas of the economy.
   He said results of the reforms began to become visible in the
third quarter of 1988 with more consumer goods and foodstuffs
available, less strain in the grain supply and a slowing of the
rate of price increases.
</TEXT>
