<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs separate moved on Korn as a0585</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Franklin A. Korn</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Franklin A. Korn, an inventor with Bell
Telephone Laboratories who helped create a nation of direct
long-distance, touch-tone phone dialers, died of kidney failure
Friday at age 83.
   Korn was director of telephone laboratories at the former
Western Electric plant in Columbus, which now is owned by AT&amp;T.
   He was credited with developing a nationwide direct-dial
military telephone network during World War II, and with the
development of touch-tone dialing.
   He also co-invented the major switching system used by telephone
companies until the mid-1970s, when electronic switching was
introduced, said Harold Heckendorn of Worthington, retired
engineering manager of the Western Electric plant.
   Korn retired from Bell Labs in 1970 after 50 years with the
company.
</TEXT>
