<FIRST>r w AM-Gridiron 1stLd-Writethru a0517 04-01 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gridiron, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Lampooned as `Pistol-Packin' Poppy' at Annual Gridiron Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new 2nd graf; INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs 3rd graf bgng
``By tradition, ...'' to update with Bush, Quayle and first lady participation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington's journalistic establishment
lampooned President Bush at a white-tie dinner Saturday night as a
``pistol-packin' poppy'' whose idea of a kinder, gentler nation is
``a cop on ev'ry corner and a gun in ev'ry hand.''
   Bush's wife Barbara nearly stole the show with a grand entrance.
Her snowy white hair was covered with a golden brown wig making the
woman known as ``The Silver Fox'' almost unrecognizable.
   Bush and Vice President Dan Quayle were prime targets of the
104-year-old Gridiron Club, whose annual dinner is one of the
biggest social events in the capital. The main business of the
evening was to spoof the president and other prominent figures with
humor designed to ``singe but never burn.''
   By tradition, the responses by Bush and Quayle to the club
members' satirical barbs were off the record.
   Yet just as traditionally that rule is ignored.
   Bush cracked ``people say I'm undecisive. I don't know about
that.'' Belittling his own skill at humor Bush said that if he had
been funnier than Ronald Reagan in 1980 _ when the two men competed
for the Republican presidential nomination _ it would have been
Reagan who was ``up here tonight trying to laugh off the Bush
deficit.''
   Quayle was the target of many jokes about his inexperience
however he said that Bush recently praised his maturity and sense
of responsibility by saying ``would you like a puppy'' from the
brood delivered by first dog Millie.
   More than 600 invited guests included the journalists' bosses
and a cross-section of the Washington power elite, including
Supreme Court justices, Cabinet members, members of Congress,
governors and foreign ambassadors and their wives.
   Gridiron president Lawrence M. O'Rourke of the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch set the irreverent tone for the evening. Commenting
good-naturedly on accomplishments of the Bush presidency, he asked
in a prepared speech, ``What previous administration could say
after 100 days that it had a new horseshoe pit?''
   Then club members, portraying their victims in a series of
satirical skits, roasted Bush, Quayle and other prominent figures,
including Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, former Texas John
Tower, House Speaker Jim Wright, White House chief of staff John
Sununu, billionaire developer Donald Trump and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
   A highlight of the prepared script was Barbara Bush, played by
Cheryl Arvidson of the Dallas Times Herald, who chided her husband
for his initial opposition to controls on semiautomatic assault
weapons.
   ``Lay that Uzi down, George, lay that Uzi down,'' sang the
on-stage Mrs. Bush. ``Pistol-packin' poppy, lay that Uzi down.''
   Later, a journalist posing as a White House speechwriter sang
the ``Bush Battle Hymn'' with these words:
   ``Mine eyes have seen the glory of a kinder, gentler land,
   ``With a cop on ev'ry corner and a gun in ev'ry hand.
   ``Tiny tots in public schools will pledge allegiance on command,
   ``George Bush is in command.''
   Then the Gridiron chorus sang: ``Sis-boom-bah and hallelujah,
Eli Yale will boola-boo ya. Read my lips so I can rule ya. You
gotta read them right.''
   Quayle, played by Richard Cooper of the Los Angeles Times, took
his lumps in a duet with former President Nixon, portrayed by John
Hall of Media General.
   To the tune of ``I Believe In You,'' the Nixon stand-in sang:
   ``You're not the dim bulb I had been led to believe I would see.
   ``Are you an airhead dilettante lightweight? You sure could fool
me.
   ``Cause I believe in you, I believe in you.
   ``I think you're perfectly qualified,
   ``As the Veep, you're swell.
   ``All my concerns have been mollified
   ``If Bush stays well.''
   To which the chorus responds: ``George, stay well.''
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential candidate who lost the
November election to Bush, was portrayed as Elvis Presley arriving
at St. No Where Hospital for a personality transplant.
   Joined by dancers in prison stripes, Dukakis sang a hip-swinging
version of ``Jailhouse Rock'' in which he lamented the day he gave
inmate Willie Horton a weekend furlough. Bush made the
Massachusetts prison furlough program a major campaign issue
against Dukakis.
   Two new active members, James M. Perry of the Wall Street
Journal and Robert Adams of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, were
initiated into the 60-member club at Saturday's dinner, held in the
Capital Hilton Hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
