<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-Week'sBusiness Adv01-02   04-01 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 01-02,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions April 1-2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix numbering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Just When You Thought the Airline Business Was Settling Down...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines is mostly mothballed, and
Northwest Airlines is flying. But both are attracting bids from
billionaire business celebrities ranging from hoteliers to
Hollywood investors.
   People who saw ``Wall Street'' may have thought they were
watching real-life variants of the back-room maneuvering for the
movie's fictional Bluestar Airlines if they followed accounts of
Eastern and Northwest this past week.
   The cast of contenders included baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth, Hyatt hotel chain owner Jay Pritzker, property-casino
centurion Donald Trump and energy-entertainment investor Marvin
Davis.
   Others said to be involved, either as buyers or their lenders,
included takeover strategist Carl Icahn, who also is chairman of
Trans World Airlines, reclusive West Coast financier Kirk
Kerkorian, and David Batchelder, the former adviser to the dean of
the corporate stalkers, oilman T. Boone Pickens.
   Miami-based Eastern remained comatose, its fate unclear, planes
mostly grounded and assets increasingly mired in bankruptcy court
proceedings, with little sign from parent Texas Air Corp. that a
sale was close.
   A group led by Ueberroth had offered $464 million offer for the
airline, which prior to the March 4 strike flew 100,000 passengers
daily to 118 cities with 250 jetliners. Since then it has barely
managed a skeleton schedule.
   Pritzker reportedly offered a higher price, value unknown. But
Ueberroth's offer told a story in itself about the perceived worth
of Eastern, one of the nation's most unprofitable airlines.
   The Ueberroth deal was $200 million below the price Texas Air
paid three years ago, and barely $100 million over what Trump had
offered for Eastern's Northeast shuttle, which flies to only three
cities with about 20 planes.
   At Minneapolis-based Northwest, meanwhile, management was facing
a $2.7 billion, $90-a-share takeover offer from Davis, a second
offer of undisclosed value from a group the airline wouldn't
identify, and rumors that at least one other investor group was
preparing to make a bid.
   Not coincidentally, Northwest's parent company NWA Inc. erected
an anti-takeover ``poison pill'' shield to thwart unfriendly
acquirers by making it prohibitively expensive for them to sell any
of the airline's assets.
   The defense was designed to foil what many analysts have called
the airline's biggest weakness: lucrative operations in the
economically booming Asian Pacific region and a lagging domestic
business.
   As the 1980s takeover era has shown, that kind of unwieldy,
inefficient performance invites unsolicited offers from investors
who see profit in selling a company in pieces.
   A takeover of Northwest therefore raised the prospect of the
biggest airline bustup since deregulation, only three years after
NWA acquired hometown rival Republic Airlines for $884 million.
   In other business and economic developments this past week:
   _After months of rumor, a federal grand jury indicted Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. junk-bond pioneer Michael Milken and two
others in the biggest fraud and racketeering case in Wall Street
history. The defendants asserted innocence in a case that reflected
the radical use of racketeering laws to prosecute white-collar
suspects. It also created a forum for a courtroom fight between
Milken and his main accuser, imprisoned speculator Ivan F. Boesky.
   _More evidence emerged of a slowing economy. The Commerce
Department said the index of leading indicators fell 0.3 percent in
February, largely because of a drop in factory orders and
construction. The department also said home sales tumbled 9.4
percent in February.
   _A stunning failure and a surprise merger proposal roiled the
banking industry, reflecting the economy's disjointed regional
growth. Federal regulators seized most of Texas-based MCorp.'s 25
banks after it disclosed plans to seek Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection. North Carolina's NCNB Corp. offered to acquire
Georgia's Citizens &amp; Souther Corp. in a stock-swap that would
create the country's sixth-largest banking company.
   _A monster Alaskan oil slick from a leaking Exxon Corp. tanker
that ran aground threatened the state's economy and coastal
wildlife. The nation's largest oil company fired the tanker's
skipper after saying tests showed he was legally drunk but faced a
torrent of criticism for its slow reaction to the worst oil spill
in U.S. history.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv weekend editions April 1-2</NOTE>
</DOC>
