<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv01-02   04-01 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 01-02,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions April 1-2</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Positive, But Wary First Quarter For Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market overcame a welter of worries to
post some respectable gains in the first quarter of 1989.
   But misgivings about the financial and economic outlook are
still very much in evidence as Wall Streeters look ahead to the
remaining nine months of tho 10 percent range. If that kind of pace
could be sustained over a year or two, it would qualify as a robust
bull market.
   Yet little rejoicing has been heard in the investment community,
which still evidently hasn't quite gotten over the shock of the
crash that occurred a year and a half ago.
   ``Since the great crash there has been no consistent theme or
trend,'' said Edward Nicoski at Piper, Jaffray &amp; Hopwood Inc. He
describes the current mood of investors as one of ``pessimistic
hope.
   ``The pessimism calls for a slowing economy and rising
unemployment, whereas the hope is embedded in the belief this will
cool inflation, diminish our trade imbalance and lower interest
rates.
   ``The unlikelihood of all the preceding happening without a
meaningful recession and sharply lower corporate profits has not
gone unnoticed, however.''
   Increased recession worries were evident from the behavior of
diversified manufacturing, auto and machinery stocks, all of which
ranked among the 10 worst performing industry groups for the
quarter.
   In a compilation through March 29, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said
the manufacturing group was down 3.8 percent; the auto stocks
dropped 2.6 percent, and the machinery group lost 1.5 percent.
   Over the same period, S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index rose 5.3
percent, not counting dividends.
   Earnings worries, meanwhile, weighed heavily on technology
stocks. The computer systems, electronic instrument, communications
equipment and semiconductor groups all finished in the minus column.
   Some of the big winners _ such as the airlines, up 17.8 percent,
and hospital management, up 20.2 percent _ got a lift from the
continuing boom in takeover and buyout bids.
   For its part, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, with a
50.58 rise to 2,293.62 in the past week, closed out the quarter
sporting a gain of 125.05 points, or 5.77 percent.
   Other readings for the week showed the New York Stock Exchange
composite index up 2.99 at 165.63; the NASDAQ composite index for
the over-the-counter market up 5.79 at 406.73, and the American
Stock Exchange market value index up 3.44 at 328.31.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 146.91 million shares a day,
against 148.40 million the week before.
   The crux of the market's problems right now, many analysts
agree, is persistently high interest rates.
   ``The current environment, in any historical perspective, is
unattractive for equities,'' said Edward Kerschner at PaineWebber
Inc.
   ``First, the relative safety of a guaranteed 10 percent one-year
return stacks up well against the returns the equity market MIGHT
deliver, even in the most benign environment.
   ``Second, the impact that these higher interest rates have in
both depressing the corporate revenue line and increasing the
corporate expense line suggests that the profit environment over
the next few quarters might be far from benign.
   ``High interest rates have historically been a harbinger of a
risky stock market, because they have been lead indicators of
earnings disappointments.''
   End Adv Weekend Editions for April 1-2
</TEXT>
